1. e4
1. e5( { As a Chigorin adept in the Ruy Lopez, I found it confusing to hear all the contradictory and negative messages thrown in at press conferences about my love baby.    This opening would have had its best time and  Dubov  even praised  Rapport  for his courage to play such a dubious opening! Stockfish mistakenly evaluates White's space advantage with astonishingly appraisals such as +1.00 (as in the King's Indian)!    In contrast to  Dubov 's pessimistic view, the Chigorin served me excellently throughout my chess career. When I drew  Nigel Short  in the Wijk aan Zee Tata Steel tournament 2009, he told me in the post-mortem that I have mastered these types of positions in this delicate strategic opening really well.    And didn't  Hansen  recently gradually outplay  Magnus Carlsen  with the black pieces in the Chigorin? Moreover, the engine with the more human touch, Leela, is giving more realistic evaluations often close to equality.    After months of painstaking monks work, I can stand up with my hand on my heart, by saying without wavering: the Chigorin provides us with equal chances!    Out of the opening in the 4 variations, I am serving you:     The Keres Defense   }1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O Be7 6.Re1 b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 O-O 9.h3 Na5 10.Bc2 c5 11.d4 Nd7 { ,     The Panov Variation   }11...Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 { ,     The Zagoriansky Variation   }11...Qc7 12.Nbd2 Be6!? { ,     The Accelerated Chigorin   }1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O Be7 6.Re1 b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 Na5 { , postponing short castling.    We obtain positions in which there is plenty of space for manoeuvring and fighting for an advantage.    My vision for the Lifetime Repertoire for Black is to give you something that could really last you a lifetime.  1.e4 e5  stood test of time, and the overoptimistic engine evaluations in the Chigorin can even mislead our opponents!    Let the battle begin! } )
2. Nf3( 2.Nc3 Nf6! { In My Lifetime Repertoire, I have constantly looked for the most direct and easy way to play and remember our plans without the risk of having to find engine-generated moves ourselves during a game. We intend to encounter the Vienna Gambit }3.f4 { with }3...d5 { , seeking the frontal confrontation in the center. } )( {   }3.Bc4 { is conveniently met by }3...Nxe4! { . To my surprise, this is called the 'Dracula-Frankenstein Variation'. }4.Nxe4 d5!=+ { is an easy solution. } )( { A better option for White after   }3...d5 { is }4.fxe5 { , when }4...Nxe4 5.Qf3!? { is very topical. }5...Nc6! ( { In another  1.e4 e5  LTR on Chessable, the difficult line }5...f5 { is recommended. I have seen my students struggling with the line }6.d3 Nxc3 7.bxc3 d4 { - White has quick piece play and the black king isn't safe anywhere. } )6.Bb5 Nxc3 7.dxc3 Qh4+! 8.g3 Qe4+ { after the exchange of queens, we obtain an easy-to-play position with the bishop pair and winning chances. ½-½ (60),  Rapport  (2745) -  Aronian  (2745), Warsaw 2023. } )( { Against the King's Gambit }2.f4 { , we fight for the initiative with the excellent response }2...d5! { , the so-called Falkbeer Countergambit. } )
2. Nc6
3. Bb5( {  Part B  of this repertoire encompasses the Italian Opening }3.Bc4 { . }{ With }3...Bc5!? { we avoid   }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . }{   }4.b4 ( 4.c3 Nf6 5.d3 ( 5.d4 { The Greco Gambit } )4...h6!? { We ruled out all of White's popular  Bg5  lines in one go. The theory is still developing, and White is trying to find ways to profit from Black's early ... h6 . Nonetheless this is not so easy since this little pawn move is useful in almost all Italian positions. Moreover, it serves us excellent - compared to the other main lines with  5...a6  or  5...a5  - there is little to know. } )4...Bxb4 { the Evans Gambit. }5.c3  )( 3.d4 exd4 4.Nxd4 ( 4.Bc4 Nf6 5.e5 d5 6.Bb5 Ne4 7.Nxd4 Bd7 8.Bxc6 bxc6 9.O-O Bc5 10.f3 Ng5 11.f4 Ne4 12.Be3 Qb8= { Black is scoring well in this relatively new line. We plan to build up the pressure on the long diagonal. } )4...Nf6! { 4... Bc5  is the other main line, however, this line is not as 'clean' as there are still many loose ends. White still has many options to explore. }5.Nxc6 { The prelude of chapter C: the Scotch opening! The prelude of chapter C: the Scotch opening! }( 5.Nc3 Nxe4! { I was shocked when I saw my student playing this line during the Dutch Championships. I interrogated him about whether he should play in such an all-or-nothing approach in this opening... there were more solid and easy ways of handling, weren't there? }6.Nxe4 Qe7! { As it seemed he was well informed and obtained an excellent position in the main line of this fascinating new line. }7.f3 d5 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.Bxc6 bxc6 10.O-O dxe4 11.Re1 O-O-O 12.Rxe4 Qb4! { Again a very recent and popular line for Black. Again a very recent and popular line for Black. }13.Nb3 Qb7 14.Qe2 Bd6 15.Be3 Rhe8 16.Rxe8 Rxe8 17.Qf2 Qb5∓ { Black was much better - due to his active pieces in: 1-0 (45) Klaren,O (1878)-Van Egmond, T (1672) Almelo 2022 } )5...bxc6 6.e5 Qe7 { Pinning twice. }7.Qe2 Nd5 8.c4 Ba6 { No, 3 times! }9.b3 g6 10.f4 d6 { Entering a long and interesting line with chances for both sides. All in all, this 4..Nf6 line has an impeccable reputation and is to be seen as the 'refutation' of the Scotch, equalising. } )
