11. Qc7( 11...Nd7 { The so-called Keres defense. }12.Nbd2 ( 12.d5 { is another line, analyzed in  Chapter A2.  } )12...exd4 13.cxd4 Nc6 { One of the key ideas of the Keres defense is to take on  d4 , after which Black obtains excellent piece play by  Bf6  and  Ne5 / c5 . }14.d5 ( 14.Nf1 cxd4 15.Nxd4 Nxd4 16.Qxd4 Ne5⇆ { threatening  Bxh3  and  Nxf3 , planning on moving the bishop to  f6  where it thrives over the long diagonal! } )14...Nce5 15.Nxe5 Nxe5 16.f4 Ng6 17.Nf3 17...Bh4!! { A stunning move, steering our once worst piece - the black squared bishop - to  g3 , provoking  f4 - f5 , after which we can use the central square  e5  for our pieces! }18.Rf1 Bg3 19.f5 Ne5 { with a double-edged game and excellent winning chances for us as our pawn structure is better. } )
12. Nbd2( 12.d5 { Thus, White is choosing colour closing the position. Frequently people ask me whether the Chigorin is still playable for Black. This kind of question was never asked me while I played my 'Chigorins' 15 years ago and has everything to do with the engine's influence. }12...Bd7 { In this type of position, Stockfish evaluates the positions as almost +1, a sign and cause of the decreasing popularity of the variation. Black's results are quite OK here. And, relating to this LTR after having seen at least more than 100 games in the main lines, I can assure you of its reliability, dear readers. Lying ahead of you is a man-to-man fight with a 50% chance of success, depending on the quality of your moves of course! :) }13.b3 { Another attempt to prevent counterplay on the queenside. For instance, in case of  b5 - b4  White can seal the structure through  c3 - c4 . }13...Rfb8 { This move may seem overly ambitious regarding Black's intentions on the queenside. However Black's main idea is to find a convenient place for his knight on  a5 . }14.Nbd2 Nb7 15.Nf1 Nd8 { My plan is beginning to take shape. The knights are on their way to  f7  and  g7 , in line with the famous set-up in one of the games of my former trainer and former Dutch champion in 1966, Eddie Scholl. }16.g4 Ne8 { Black is falling back on this 5-decade-old plan, moving the knights to  g7  and  f7 . }17.Ng3 g6 18.Kh2 f6 19.Be3 { Yup, still +1. 00 given by the most recent version of Stockfish! Leela is more realistic and is navigating towards a minimal plus for White. Given my experience here I'd rather say it's an equal position. }19...Nf7 { All part of the plan, which has almost been accomplished. }20.Rg1 Kh8 21.Nd2 Bf8 { Black defended his king's defenses perfectly. The knights cover all the squares, while white's main blow, i.e.  Nf5 , has been defused. }22.Nf5!? { Playing on stage at Wijk Aan Zee, I can still recall that Daniel and I were being mocked by the top players like Kramnik and Aronian about (A) the sacrifice, and (B) the denial of the sacrifice by not taking it. }22...c4!? ( 22...gxf5? { as the engine claims, the acceptance of this sacrifice is highly risky. }23.gxf5 Ng7 24.Qg4 { followed by the tripling of the heavy pieces, is granting White the superior chances. } )23.Rg3?! ( 23.bxc4! { would have been would have been better. }23...bxc4 24.Ng3 24...Rb2⩲  )23...cxb3 { Now Black obtains his so desired counterplay on the queenside. }24.axb3 Qxc3!? { This involves a queen sacrifice. ½-½  Stellwagen  (2585) -  Werle  (2566), Wijk aan Zee 2007. The rest of the  analysis  can be seen in the Model Game section. } )
