11. Bxe6
11. fxe6{ Can we say that these double pawns are weakening our structure?     My first coach taught me that the pawn on  e6  covers the important central squares  f5  and  d5 . Later on, I was greatly influenced - sitting next to him - by an impressive positional siege of  Jorden van Foreest  (vs. Lobzhanidze). And so, a couple of decades later, and after many years of wisdom (really??), I am totally clueless! }
