4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. d3{ The so-called Anderssen Variation should be taken seriously, not in the last place because it's played by all the world-class players (from time to time), such as Carlsen, Caruana, Anand, Rapport and so on. On the other hand, I don't think we should be too afraid of this line since we have not yet committed our bishop to  e7 , and can nail it on the more active  c5 -square! }
5. b5{ Please take into account the threat of  Bxc6  and  Nxe5 . We are stopping this once and for all with  5...b5 . }
6. Bb3
6. Bc5( { Since White committed to the somewhat passive  5.d3 , this active bishop move is very to the point. White now has a broad choice of moves, like }7.Bg5 { , }7.c3 { , }7.a4 { , }7.O-O { and }7.Nc3 { . } )
7. Nc3( { At this point, there are many ways to reach the  7.O-O  variation. Let's cover those move orders here:      }7.h3 d6 8.c3 O-O 9.O-O { ,      }7.h3 d6 8.O-O O-O 9.c3 { ,      }7.c3 d6 8.O-O O-O 9.h3 { . } )
7. h6{ In these  Nc3  lines, be alert on White's main idea of  Nd5  and  Bg5 . }
8. Nd5
8. d6
