9. Rb8{ Prophylaxis against both  a4  and  Nxf6  and  Bd5 . }
10. O-O
10. O-O{ We shouldn't act rashly by taking on  d5 . Instead, we complete our development first. }
11. Re1( { We can handle }11.Be3 { without facing significant danger. }11...Nxd5 12.Bxd5 Bxe3 { The mass exchanges result in a balanced position. }13.fxe3 Ne7= { Anand had obtained equal chances in  Vachier Lagrave  (2775) -  Anand  (2764), ½-½ (34), Paris 2019. } )( 11.Bc2 Ba7 12.h3 Re8 ( 12...Be6 { is also playable. }13.Nxf6+ Qxf6 14.Be3 { , ½-½ (47),  Anton Guijarro  (2691) - Mamedyarov  (2759), chess24.com 2022. } )13.Be3 Nxd5 14.exd5 Bxe3 15.fxe3 Ne7 16.e4 Ng6= { Following with ... Bd7  and ... c6 , we obtain equal chances. } )( 11.h3 Nxd5 { Again, we can ease our task to equalise by swapping off the knight. }12.exd5 Ne7 13.d4 exd4 14.Nxd4 Bd7 15.Re1 Ng6⩱ { 1-0 (82),  Urazayev  (2451) -  Pichot    (2628), chess.com 2021. } )
11. Nxd5{ Now it's time to take, immediately improving the knight to  g6 . }
12. exd5
12. Ne7
13. d4{ It seems like White obtains something. However, due to our strong  c5 -bishop outside the pawn chain, we have plenty of active play. }
13. exd4
14. Nxd4
14. Bd7{ Black is set for freeing himself by  Nf5 . In case White is stopping this by  Qf3 , we can deploy the knight via  g6  on  e5 . }( 14...Re8 { is playable but after }15.Bd2 { , the  e8 -rook is momentarily a bit misplaced. }15.Be3?! { was played in  Anand  (2751) -  Mamedyarov  (2767), ½-½ (40), Baku 2021. }15...Bd7 { Black gets a good game. }16.Qf3 Bxd4 17.Bxd4 Nf5 18.Be3 Nxe3 19.Rxe3 Qg5⩱ { There is too much space behind the enemy lines. } )
15. Be3( { Black gets plenty of active options after }15.Qf3 Ng6! { ⩱ }{ . } )
15. Nf5{ Black is totally fine. }( { After }16.Nxf5?! Bxf5 17.Bxc5 dxc5⩱ { the  d5 -pawn is weak. } )
