1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. c3{ White doesn't have to reveal their intentions yet; by starting with  4.c3 , they can still choose to play  d3  or  d4  on their next move. }
4. Nf6
5. d4{ We are entering the fray of the so-called Greco Gambit, named after mister  Greco  who played it first and gained 4 convincing victories in this system in 1620. The line became 'salonfähig' recently, with many elite players giving this dangerous line a shot. }
5. exd4
6. cxd4
6. Bb4+( { Gaining an important tempo in order to instantly strike back in the center by ... d7 - d5 , or take the pawn on  e4 . White has now three main moves: }7.Nc3 { , }7.Nbd2 { , and }7.Bd2 { . Actually, all contain venom. } )
7. Bd2
7. Nxe4( { Also playable is }7...Bxd2+ 8.Nbxd2 d5 { , breaking the center. }9.exd5 Nxd5 { , with some complications arising after }10.Qb3 { . ½-½ (14),  So  (2778) -  Nakamura  (2736), chess24. com 2021. } )
8. Bxb4
8. Nxb4{ The knights are unprotected and this could give an insecure feeling. True, but there ain't no such thing as a free lunch. And I can tell you dear reader, this pawn on  e4  was very tasty! }
9. Bxf7+{ White is making a committing move in order to win the pawn back. }
9. Kxf7
10. Qb3+{ In these days where the engines predominate, presumably you are surprised to hear that we are still in the game of Greco, played in 1620. }
10. d5{ Logically, Greco's opponent went for this developing move. }
11. Ne5+
11. Ke6{ This move is impossible to find without the help of our silicon friend. Luckily, we have the MoveTrainer! }( 11...Kg8?! 12.Qxb4 Qf6 13.O-O c5? { is too much the position can handle. }14.Qb5 b6 15.Qe8+ Qf8 16.Qc6 { and after a series of inaccurate and over-optimistic moves, Black throws in the towel. }16...Ba6 17.Qxd5+ Qf7 18.Qxf7# { , 1-0 (18),  Greco  -  NN , Europe 1620. } )
12. Qxb4
12. Qf8{ Naturally, we ought to exchange the queens with the king on  e6 . }
13. Qxf8
13. Rxf8
14. f3
14. Nd6
15. Nc3
15. Nf7{ Exchanging White's strongest piece! }( { Black had to endure some difficulties after }15...Nf5 16.Rd1 c6 17.Kf2 Kd6 18.Rhe1 g5 19.g4 Nh4 20.Kg3⩲ { , 1-0 (52),  So  (2772) -  Aronian  (2782), chess24.com 2021. } )
16. O-O
16. Nxe5{ White can win the pawn back and has numerous ways of doing that. }
17. Rae1( 17.Rfe1?! Rf5!?  )
17. c6{ This position needs to be tested. White can follow up with  f4  or  Rxe5  followed by doubling on the e-file. }
18. Rxe5+
18. Kd6{ Black equalized comfortably, as his king is already centralized and he has every chance on getting something out of his queenside majority. }
