7. O-O( { Mr. Paul Morphy himself was the first ever to encounter the Göring Gambit! }7.h3?! { Stopping ... Bg4 , but way too slow. }7...Be6! { Defusing the threat across the diagonal. }8.Bb5 Nge7! { Black is much better and Morphy went on to win, 0-1 (31),  Meek  -  Morphy , New York 1857. } )( { Occupying the  g5 -square is not great for White: }7.Bg5 Nge7! { after which we shouldn't worry about  Ng5  any longer. } )
7. Nf6
8. Bg5
8. h6{ Trying to get rid of the pin. }
9. Bxf6{ Giving up on the pin, but a series of powerful moves follow. }
9. Qxf6
10. Nd5
10. Qd8
11. b4{ The danger hasn't been averted yet. }
11. Bb6( 11...Bxb4? { is just bad, because of }12.Nxb4 Nxb4 13.Qb3→ { with a double attack. } )
12. a4
12. Ne5
13. Nxe5
13. dxe5
14. Qh5
14. Bd4{ A very important move! Black should not give up his extra pawn so easily. }( { Worse is }14...O-O? 15.Nxb6 axb6 16.Qxe5⩲ { . White might be slightly better here, as Black has some small issues to solve. } )
15. Nb6{ This crude discovered attack, hitting  f7  and  a8 , can be met by the simple castling and counting of the pieces. }
15. O-O
16. Nxa8
16. Bxa1{ The knight won't run, but even so, we are aiming for a double attack improving our pieces first. }
17. Rxa1
17. Qd4
18. Rc1
18. Be6{ A fine observation, if you noticed that we ended up in a correspondence game, and actually, even 5 correspondence games have been played from this position. }( 19.Bxe6 fxe6 { with the counterthreat on  f2 . }20.h3 Qxf2+⇆ { ½-½ (25),  Hardyn  (1734) -  Herzog  (1751), LSS email 2016. } )
