5. Bc4{ The so-called 'Double Pawn Sacrifice Variation' of the Göring Gambit. White is offering the second pawn on  b2 , aiming to take back with the other bishop. White gets serious compensation as his 3 minor pieces occupy active positions. }
5. d6{ At first sight, this move may seem too passive... but better safe than sorry! 😀 }( { My good friend and fellow Chessable author GM Erwin L'Ami went for another pawn during the Olympiad: }5...cxb2 6.Bxb2 Bb4+ 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.O-O Bxc3 9.Bxc3 d6 { , 0-1 (27),  El Jawich  (2276) -  L'Ami  (2639), Batumi 2018, but despite the fact that Black is 2 pawns up, the engines deem this position as slightly better for White after }10.Ng5! O-O 11.f4→ { with a dangerous attack. } )
6. Nxc3
6. Nf6
7. Qb3{ These positions are somewhat similar to the Evans gambit. Black uses the same idea here, guarding  f7 . }( 7.O-O Be7 { transposes to  6.O-O . } )( 7.e5 { would be a bit premature. }7...dxe5 8.Qxd8+ ( 8.Qb3 Qd7 { transposes. } )8...Nxd8 9.Nxe5 Bd6∓ { Black is a pawn up. } )
7. Qd7{ However strange-looking, this queen move is also seen in the Evans Gambit. At first sight, the queen is misplaced on  d7 . The point is that we aim for a quick ... Qg4  while paving the way to eliminate White's strongest piece: the  c4 -bishop (... Nc6 - a5 ). }
8. e5
8. dxe5{ The position looks terribly frightening. However, if White plays too slowly then Black is fine after ... Bd6  and ... O-O . }
9. Ng5
9. Nd4{ As it appears, we can handle White's bashing at  f7 . }( { Only }9...Nd8 { was tried before. } )
10. Bxf7+( 10.Qd1 Qc6! { followed by taking on  g2 . } )
10. Ke7
11. Qb4+( 11.Qd1 h6 { White loses material. } )
11. Kd8{ There is no defense against ... Nc2 ( + ). }
