[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Bc4{ We are entering the fray the Scotch Gambit entails. Rather than recapturing the pawn on  d4 , white aims to develop his bishop and take aim at the  f7 -pawn. }
4. Nf6( 4...Bc5 { is also perfectly playable, but I'd rather keep it simple by avoiding the move }5.Ng5 { . }5...Nh6 6.Nxf7!? { is commonly played at the highest level }{ ( }6...Nxf7 7.Bxf7+ Kxf7 8.Qh5+ g6 9.Qxc5∞ { ) }{ . } )
5. e5
5. d5{ We are standing our ground in the fight for the center, providing a foothold for the knight at  e4 . }
6. Bb5( 6.exf6? { is simply bad for White: }6...dxc4 7.O-O Qxf6-+ { . } )( { Not much better is }6.exd6?! Bxd6 { White accelerated our development. }7.O-O O-O { Black is a healthy pawn up. } )
6. Ne4{ Knights need a foothold in the center, as the old and wise chess proverb goes. }
7. Nxd4
7. Bd7{ We are following the old theoretical path to equality. }( 7...Bc5 { is definitely playable but less to my taste. }8.Be3 { White gets some extra options here, such as postponing short castling, immediately undermining the central knight. }8...O-O !? ( 8...Bd7 9.Bxc6 bxc6 10.Nd2! { Undermining the knight before castling. } )9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.Bxc5 Nxc5 11.Bxc6 { With a complicated game ahead }{ , 1-0 (29),  Jones  (2672) -  Lei  (2535), chess24.com 2022. } )
8. Bxc6
8. bxc6{ Doubling the pawns, raising concerns about our pawn structure? Not really, as we get the bishop pair in return. }
9. O-O( { Chasing the knight away without castling cannot be recommended: }9.f3 Qh4+!-+ { . } )
9. Bc5{ The contours are taking shape. Black puts the bishop at  b6 , castles short and will try to play ... c6 - c5 . }( { I deem the following line as too risky: }9...Be7 10.f3 Nc5 11.f4 O-O 12.f5∞ { Entering an unclear position, 0-1 (51),  Vocaturo  (2598) -  Gledura  (2605), Barcelona 2017. } )
10. f3
10. Ng5{ The tension is flaring up across the diagonal  a7 - g1 . }
11. Kh1
11. Ne6{ Undermining the strong  d4 -knight. }
12. c3
12. O-O
13. f4
13. Bxd4{ An interesting, active reaction to White's dangerous plan of advancing the f-pawn. }
14. cxd4
14. c5{ Opening the light squares. }
15. dxc5
15. Bb5{ Black created a passed pawn and has active pieces. }
