6. a5{ Although this move is not commonly used, I decided to choose it over the other 6(!) more popular moves. The reason for my decision will be explained in the selected games.    By making this move, the knight gains the freedom to move to  a4  without leaving  e4  vulnerable, which allows for a trade with the powerful  c5 -bishop.     Duda  and  Yu  Yanghi have demonstrated that choosing  6...a5  instead of the more commonly used  6...a6  can lead to Black benefiting from future expansion on the queenside. }( 6...a6 7.O-O O-O 8.Kh1 Ng4 9.Qe1 f5!?∞ { , 0-1 (85),  Wei Yi  (2736) -  Firouzja  (2682), chess.com 2019. } )
7. O-O
7. h6
8. b3{ A bit of a peculiar move from  Rapport , as it weakens the dark squares. The point is that he is stopping ... a5 - a4  for now. }
8. O-O{ We can reach this position with different move orders. However, staying flexible could send our opponent off in the wrong direction. }
9. h3
9. Nd4
10. Be3
10. c6{ This inclusion is useful. We take the  d5 -square away from White, whereas we are poised to resume with ... d6 - d5  or ... b7 - b5 . }
11. Kh2
11. Re8{  Duda  is commencing with his preparations to launch ... d6 - d5 . }
12. Ne2( { In case of }12.a4 { , impeding Black's advance on the queenside, Black strikes in the center with }12...d5⩱ { . } )
12. Nxf3+{ Mass exchanges follow. As seen in the  Rapport - Duda  game (2022), the doubling of pawns weakens White's position. }
13. Bxf3
13. Bxe3
14. fxe3
14. a4{ Once again, the further push of the a-pawn on the 6th move, has proven its value. }
