[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bb5{ White's plan is, sooner or later, to take on  c6  and enjoy a structural plus. Compared to the Ruy Lopez,  central pawn breaks ( c3 + d4 ) are less common in the Four Knights Spanish, and instead, it often leads to more closed and manoeuvring games. }
4. Nd4{ We enter the 'Rubinstein Variation', named after the great  Akiba Rubinstein  - one of the great players in chess history (like  Paul Keres  and  Viktor Korchnoi ) who played at World Champion level but never got the title.    An old line, played in the late 19th century by the pioneers Marshall, Schlechter and Blackburne. This variation is to my taste as it seeks activity, breaking the symmetry. Black takes the lead while the bishop is somewhat misplaced on  b5 . }( { The main line and the only one I always have played, was }4...Bb4 5.O-O O-O 6.d3 d6 7.Bg5 Bxc3 8.bxc3 Qe7 9.Re1 Nd8!? { One of the key ideas - bringing the knight to the strong  e6 -square. }10.d4 Bg4 { My pet line.  10...Ne6  is more common. }11.h3 Bh5 12.g4 Bg6 13.d5 c6 14.Bd3 ( 14.Bc4 Rc8 15.Re3 cxd5 16.Bxd5 Ne6⩱ { , 0-1 (40),  Willemze  (2414) -  Werle  (2552), Netherlands 2007. } )14...Rc8 15.c4 b6= { ½-½ (66),  Adams  (2699) -  Werle  (2575), London 2009. } )
5. Bc4{ The other main option for White, after  5.Ba4 . }
5. Bc5{ An active move, unleashing the beast, but leaving the  e5 -pawn unguarded. }( 5...d6 { would leave the  f8 -bishop restrained. } )
6. Nxe5{ Crossing the Rubicon: winning a pawn while Black is getting a dangerous initiative. }( 6.O-O d6 { Hoping for ... Bg4 . }7.Nxd4 Bxd4 8.d3 { is just equal, and very uninspiring from White's perspective. } )
6. Qe7{ A multiple-purpose move, as we not only attack the knight and  e4 -pawn but aim for long castling as well. }( { Black didn't manage to get full compensation for the pawn with }6...O-O 7.O-O d6 8.Nf3 Bg4 9.Be2 Nxe2+ 10.Qxe2 d5 11.d3 { in ½-½   Vorobiov  (2580) -  Kovalev  (2598), Lisbon 2017. } )
7. Nxf7( 7.Bxf7+ { loses a piece to }7...Kf8 8.f4 d6-+ { . } )
7. d5{ In line with our power play, opening up the files for our pieces. }
8. Nxh8
8. dxc4{ Regaining one piece. }
9. O-O( { There are more tenacious ways to defend, one way or another Black is pulling the strings. Maybe }9.h3 { is relatively best, but Black is clearly better after }9...Be6 { , simply winning the  h8 -knight. } )
9. Bg4{ So extremely powerful, this move. }
10. Qe1
10. Nxc2{ We have bad news for our opponent: not only the rook is lost, but the queen is trapped as well! }
