2. Nf6( { The most direct approach - putting pressure on the  e4 -pawn. I feel this is more to the point than }2...Nc6 { . } )
3. f4{ We have reached the main line of the Vienna Opening. There are some similarities with the King's Gambit, as White intends to open up the f-file in order to generate play across the f-file. }( 3.Nf3 Nc6 { would transpose to the Four Knights Opening. } )
3. d5{ This active approach is seen repetitively throughout this Lifetime Repertoire. We are not grabbing the pawn and subjecting ourselves to White's forthcoming initiative, but instead, we fight back in center. }
4. fxe5
4. Nxe4{ A difficult position arises. White should refrain from taking on  e4  since the isolated pawn would hinder White's development. Moreover, it would weaken the  e5 -pawn as well: the  f3 -square won't be available to White's knight anymore,  d2 - d4  could be answered by ... exd3  and our queen gains access to the  d4 -square. }
5. Nf3( { This line has disappeared from practice nowadays: }5.Qf3 { is currently fashionable. } )
5. Be7
6. Qe2
6. Nxc3{ We couldn't maintain our  e4 -knight anymore. On the bright side, White spent a tempo on attacking it with  Qe2 . }
7. dxc3{ White's  plan de campagne  is to castle queenside, ratcheting up the tension on the  d5 -pawn. }
7. c5{ I fancy the idea of remaining flexible - we can still castle to either side. }
8. Bf4
8. Nc6{ These obvious developing moves can be made before castling. }
9. O-O-O
9. Be6{ Bolstering the only weak spot in our position: the  d5 -pawn. }
10. h4
10. h6{ Preventing any future  Ng5 . }
11. g3
11. Qd7{ Preventing the exchange of bishops by  Bh3 . We still keep White in the dark on our castling intentions. }
12. Bg2
12. b5{ A modern and new approach suggested by the strongest engines! White is somewhat disorganized and has no real threats or plans. We can profit from that by the beginning of an assault on White's monarch. }( 12...O-O-O { gave Black equal chances in  Adams  (2640) -  Anand  (2720), ½-½ (24), Linares 1994. } )( 12...Rd8!? { is interesting as well, intending to push the pawn to  d4  and play for ... Nb4 . } )
13. Kb1
13. a5{ We are not wasting any time defending the pawn on  b5 . }
14. Nd2
14. O-O
15. Nf1
15. b4{ We have excellent attacking prospects, while White's threats are too slow. }( { The game could continue }16.c4 { . Attacking  d5 , but neglecting the  d4 -square. }16...Nd4!→ { Followed by ... dxc4 , sacrificing the exchange gives us an overwhelming advantage. } )
