5. Nc6{ This move liquidates into an endgame where we have at least equal chances, while we risk little to nothing. }( 5...f5 { is the most common move and was recommended by  Gustafsson  in his  1. e4 e5  Lifetime Repertoires , 2019. This variation is of course theoretically correct but in my opinion, it's very hard to play for Black. }6.d3 Nxc3 7.bxc3 d4 { Breaking the pawn chain, so far so good. }8.Qg3 Nc6 ( { After }8...dxc3 9.Be2 Nc6 10.Bh5+! g6 { can't be played because of to }11.Bxg6+ { . } )9.Be2!? { White's main idea is to put the bishop on the long diagonal. }9...Be6 10.c4 { Closing the diagonal for the  e6 -bishop. }10...Qd7 11.Bf3 { White follows up with  Ne2  and  Rb1 , which leads to highly complex position, as in  Krastev  (2402) -  Sonis  (2539), 1-0 (58), Corte 2022. } )
6. Bb5
6. Nxc3{ We have to give up our centralised knight now that it is attacked twice. }
7. dxc3
7. Qh4+{ Not only weakening the light squares on the kingside but also pressing for the exchange of queens. }
8. g3
8. Qe4+( 8...Qe7!? { is also seen in current grandmaster practice. The position is highly complex after }9.Bf4 Bd7∞ { , as in  Hong  (2504) -  Balakrishnan  (2517), ½-½, chess.com 2022. } )
9. Qxe4
9. dxe4{ This new line became quite popular lately. We have taken the sting out of White's attack by exchanging the queens, while we have the healthier pawn structure. }
10. Bxc6+
10. bxc6{ Allowing a small weakening of our pawn structure but acquiring the pair of bishops. }
11. Ne2
11. Rb8( 11...c5 { , impeding  Nd4 , is also playable (½-½ (60),  Shirov  (2704) -  Jumabayev  (2617), Chennai 2022). } )
