3. c3{ The main idea behind the Ponziani is to control the center with the pawn on  d4 . This noble endeavor, however, has a clear disadvantage: the  c3 -square is not available for the knight.    While it is not a top choice among modern grandmasters, it can be a surprise weapon and a good option for club players who want to play something different. }
3. d5{ Strike while the iron is hot! }( { White cannot use the  c3 -square for their knight to chase the queen after }4.exd5 Qxd5 { , so we are taking control in the center. } )
4. Qa4
4. Bd7{ Making use of a discovered attack. }
5. exd5
5. Nd4{ White has won a pawn, Black is gaining time. }
6. Qd1
6. Nxf3+
7. Qxf3{ The queen is vulnerable so White loses even more time retreating. }
7. Nf6{ The most crucial aspect in this line is understanding where our opportunities for attack lie, with the ultimate goal of obtaining complete compensation for the pawn that was sacrificed. }( { My next game played in the French league stresses this painfully: }7...f5? { I immediately went wrong. }8.d4! e4 9.Qd1 Nf6 10.c4 c6 11.dxc6 bxc6± { with too little compensation for the pawn. 1-0 (41),  Shirazi  (2389) -  Werle  (2514), France 2006. } )
8. Bc4{ In my opinion, this is the only dangerous continuation we can face. White is developing while he is clinging to the extra pawn. }
8. b5{ A useful intervention, as it hinders the advance of the  c3 -pawn in the long run. White will try to stick to the extra pawn on  d5 . }( { I prefer the text over }8...e4 9.Qe2 Bd6 10.d4 h6 11.Nd2 O-O 12.Nf1 b5 13.Bxb5 Nxd5⇆ { , ½-½ (30),  Abasov  (2664) -  Amin  (2695), Tornelo INT 2021. } )
9. Bb3
9. e4{ Chasing the queen while the  f8 -bishop will find its destiny at  d6 . }
10. Qe2( { After }10.Qe3 Bd6 { the queen is misplaced. For example, }11.O-O ? Bxh2+! 12.Kxh2 Ng4+ { . } )
10. Bd6{ White's king's position is troubling. Due to the pressure on  h2 , White can not castle easily. }
11. d4( { A good reaction to }11.d3 { is }11...O-O! { , simply ignoring the pawn. White would be foolish to open the position with }12.dxe4 { , because }12...Bg4 13.f3 Nxe4!! { is a nasty surprise. The queen meddles with the affairs. }14.fxg4 Qh4+ 15.Kf1 Rae8 { wins for Black. } )
11. O-O{ White's pawn mass has been halted by the pawn on  b5 . Black is poised to start a dangerous attack on the kingside. }
12. Bg5( 12.O-O ? Ng4 13.h3 Qh4→  )
12. h6{ Our target is the  d5 -pawn. Therefore we should start thinking about how to lift the pin. }
13. Bh4
13. a5{ With the aim to chase the  b3 -bishop, let go on the defense of  d5 . }
14. a3( { Other moves won't come to White's rescue either. For instance, }14.a4 g5! 15.Bg3 bxa4 16.Bxa4 ( { The attack continues after }16.Ba2 Bg4 17.Qc2 Rb8 18.O-O Nh5 19.Na3 Nf4=∞ { . } )16...Bxa4 17.Rxa4 Qd7 { Before we take on  d5 , we optimise the position of our pieces. }18.Ra1 Nxd5∓ { . } )
14. Re8{ Our plan is plain and simple, likewise as in the  14.a4  line. Now that White intends to stick to his extra pawn by moving the bishop to  a2  after  a5 - a4 , we aim for ... g5  and ... Bg4  before we improve our knight to  f4 , from where it will rule over the board. }
15. Nd2
15. g5
16. Bg3
16. Bg4
17. Qe3
17. a4{ The white pawn mass on the queenside has been stopped. }
