9. Na5{ This is the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez. The knight is temporarily steered to the edge of the board. White can't avoid to lose their best minor piece, the light-squared bishop, so they spend time manoeuvring it from  Bb3  to  c2 . This allows Black to advance their c-pawn, gaining control of the queenside and disrupting White's plans to establish a strong center with  d2 - d4 . }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally, White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Nd7{ The knight leaves its  f6 -post, clearing the path for the  e7 -bishop. Black gives up control over the  d5 -square, but White cannot use the  c3 -square (and thus  d5 ) for his knight.     An additional note: please see the lines through with Leela (which is better in this type of strategic slow positions) instead of Stockfish. }( 11...Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 { would transpose to the  Panov Defense . } )
12. d5
12. Nb6{ In these closed positions, smart strategical maneuvering is of paramount importance. For that reason, I have analyzed this type of position primarily with Leela, in order to get a 'human touch'. And I can assure you when you let 'her' run for a while, she is foreseeing a bright future for us. }
13. b3
13. f5{ One of the many benefits of the Keres's knight maneuver, is that the knight is opening the way for the advance of the f-pawn. }
14. exf5( 14.Nbd2 f4! { Seizing space and control over the kingside. Black has the better odds, for example after }15.Bd3 Bd7 16.Be2 Qe8→ { A novelty suggested by the strongest engine. The queen is directed towards White's vulnerable king. } )
14. Bxf5{ The opening of the f-file is granting Black access to White's king, as we will see soon enough. }
15. Bxf5
15. Rxf5{ Black's strategy is plain and simple: doubling and if the opportunity arises, we sac our rook on  f3 . }
16. Qd3( 16.Na3 Qd7 17.Re4 Raf8 18.c4 Rxf3 19.gxf3 Qxh3→ {  Sanal  (2571) -  Blagojevic  (2489), Niksic 2021. } )
16. Qd7{ Preparing the doubling of rooks, but targetting  h3  as well. }
17. Be3{ What else? }( { In case of }17.Nbd2 { then }17...c4 { . ⇆ } )
17. Rxf3{ Of course, the position was asking for it. }
18. gxf3
18. Qxh3{ Unnecessary to explain black's compensation.. }
19. Qe4{ Attempting to swap the queens by  Qg4 . }
19. Rf8
20. Qg4( { There is no time for }20.Nd2 { due to }20...Rf6-+ { . } )
20. Qxg4+
21. fxg4
21. Nxd5{ Black got the much better position in  Sandipan  (2510) -  Gozzoli  (2377), 1-0 (43), Goa 2002. }
