10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally, White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Nd7{ The knight leaves its  f6 -post, clearing the path for the  e7 -bishop. Black gives up control over the  d5 -square, but White cannot use the  c3 -square (and thus  d5 ) for his knight.     An additional note: please see the lines through with Leela (which is better in this type of strategic slow positions) instead of Stockfish. }( 11...Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 { would transpose to the  Panov Defense . } )
12. Nbd2
12. exd4{ This is all part of our plan. We hand over the center to our opponent, aiming for a pawn majority on the queenside. On top of that, we pressurize the central pawns across the just opened files or diagonal. }( { Another interesting option would be }12...Qc7!? 13.d5 c4 14.Nf1 Nb7 ( {  Hansen 's next game wasn't as glorious as against  Magnus  or in the game against  Duda  after  14...Nb7 . }14...Nc5 15.Ng3 Nab7 16.Be3 g6 17.Bh6 Re8 18.Qd2 f6 { with the familiar idea of bringing the knight to  f7 . 1-0 (50),  Niemann  (2642) -  Hansen  (2606), chess.com 2022. } )15.Ng3 g6! 16.Bh6 Re8 17.Qd2 Nbc5 18.b4 cxb3 19.axb3 Nb6 20.h4 Bg4 21.h5 a5 22.Nh2 Bd7 23.Qe3 a4⇆ { with counterplay for Black in this double-edged position. 0-1 (45),  Duda  (2760) -  Hansen  (2606), chess24.com 2022. } )
13. cxd4
13. Nc6{ Targetting  d4 . }
14. dxc5
14. dxc5{ The structure is being adjusted, which is in our favour. Nonetheless, we should be cautious because of White's attacking idea consisting of  e4 - e5 , followed by  Qe2 - e4 . }
15. e5
15. Bb7{ Completing the development, after we engage in the struggle revolving around the pawn on  e5 . }( { Also playable is }15...c4!? { . } )
16. Qe2
16. c4{ Vacating the  c5 -square for the knight. }
17. Qe4( { In case of }17.b3 Nb4!⇆ { is strong. } )( { Harmless is }17.e6 fxe6 18.Qxe6+ Kh8= { . } )
17. g6
18. Qf4
18. Qc7{ Besieging the central pawn on  e5 . }
19. h4
19. Ncxe5
20. Nxe5
20. Bd6
21. Ndf3
21. Nxe5
22. Nxe5
22. Rfe8{ Using the pin across the e-file. }
23. Be4
23. Rxe5{ Black won the pawn and the game, 0-1 (23),  Fuchs  (2321) -  Bacrot  (2696), Karlsruhe 2017. }
