7. d6( { After lengthy consideration, I decided to recommend }7...d6 { . }{ The other main option is }7...O-O { , after which Black can opt for ... d7 - d5  at once. }8.a4!? { is the critical continuation, when Black chooses between }8...Bb7 { , allowing White to shut the bishop out of the game by  d3 , or }8...b4 { , giving up control over the important  c4 -square. } )
8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. O-O
9. h3( 9.h3 { is the most commonly played move for good reason. It prepares the central pawn thrust  10.d4 , preventing any interference from ... Bg4 . } )( { However, }9.d4 { is entirely playable and is called the  Yates Variation . In response, we play }9...Bg4 { , the Bogoljubov Variation! } )
9. Na5{ This is the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez. The knight is temporarily steered to the edge of the board. White can't avoid to lose their best minor piece, the light-squared bishop, so they spend time manoeuvring it from  Bb3  to  c2 . This allows Black to advance their c-pawn, gaining control of the queenside and disrupting White's plans to establish a strong center with  d2 - d4 . }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally, White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Nd7{ The knight leaves its  f6 -post, clearing the path for the  e7 -bishop. Black gives up control over the  d5 -square, but White cannot use the  c3 -square (and thus  d5 ) for his knight.     An additional note: please see the lines through with Leela (which is better in this type of strategic slow positions) instead of Stockfish. }( 11...Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 { would transpose to the  Panov Defense . } )
12. Nbd2
12. exd4{ This is all part of our plan. We hand over the center to our opponent, aiming for a pawn majority on the queenside. On top of that, we pressurize the central pawns across the just opened files or diagonal. }( { Another interesting option would be }12...Qc7!? 13.d5 c4 14.Nf1 Nb7 ( {  Hansen 's next game wasn't as glorious as against  Magnus  or in the game against  Duda  after  14...Nb7 . }14...Nc5 15.Ng3 Nab7 16.Be3 g6 17.Bh6 Re8 18.Qd2 f6 { with the familiar idea of bringing the knight to  f7 . 1-0 (50),  Niemann  (2642) -  Hansen  (2606), chess.com 2022. } )15.Ng3 g6! 16.Bh6 Re8 17.Qd2 Nbc5 18.b4 cxb3 19.axb3 Nb6 20.h4 Bg4 21.h5 a5 22.Nh2 Bd7 23.Qe3 a4⇆ { with counterplay for Black in this double-edged position. 0-1 (45),  Duda  (2760) -  Hansen  (2606), chess24.com 2022. } )
13. cxd4
13. Nc6{ Targetting  d4 . }
14. d5
14. Nce5{ This position resembles to a Benoni, with the difference that we took plenty of space by moving the pawn forward to  b5 . Other than that, our bishop is not (yet) placed on the long diagonal. }
15. Nxe5( 15.Nf1 { doesn't pose many problems. }15...Nxf3+ 16.Qxf3 Ne5 17.Qe2 f5!⇆ { We fight back in the center. ½-½ (42),  Morawietz  (2449) -  Friedel  (2555), Bad Wiessee 2009. } )
15. Nxe5{ Exchanging one pair of pieces is favourable to us since we solve the limited space for our pieces maneuvring. Our adversary's plan is to drive off the knight and take control of square  e5 . }
16. f4
16. Ng6{ The knight is well placed on  g6 , engaging on the struggle in the center hitting  f4  and  e5 . }
17. Nf3( { The move }17.f5 { comes too early for White now. }17...Ne5! 18.Nf3 Bf6 { with a pleasant positional edge due to our firm control in the center. 0-1 (38),  Papadopoulos  (2256) -  Neelotpal  (2426), Paleochora 2018. } )
17. Bh4{ A stunning and indispensable counteroperation for us, while being under siege. The bishop is behind enemy lines and moved to  g3 , from where it forces  f4 - f5  leaving the  e5 -square in our hands. }
18. Nxh4
18. Qxh4
19. f5
19. Ne5{ As it happens so often with moves, there are pros and cons. White's  19.f5  immobilises our bishop at  c8 , but on the other hand, we obtain the best thinkable square for our knight on  e5 . }
20. Rf1
20. Bd7
21. Bf4{ This is by far the most dangerous move for Black. }
21. Qe7
22. Qe1
22. f6{ I truly believe that Black is better from here, although the engines grant Black only a microscopic advantage. }
23. Qg3
23. Rfe8{ The position is closed, as white's  e4 -pawn is blocked. We can rejoice the majority on the queenside. }
24. Bd1( 24.b3 a5!⩱ { Please see the  model game  section for further analysis. 0-1  Damljanovic  (2589) -  Ponomariov  (2718), Plovdiv 2003. } )
24. a5{ Part of our strategy: using our majority of pawns creating a passed pawn and counterplay. Besides we will find space there to employ our isolated bishop. }
25. Bh5
25. Rec8{ It will be hard for either side to make progress. }
