9. Na5{ This is the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez. The knight is temporarily steered to the edge of the board. White can't avoid to lose their best minor piece, the light-squared bishop, so they spend time manoeuvring it from  Bb3  to  c2 . This allows Black to advance their c-pawn, gaining control of the queenside and disrupting White's plans to establish a strong center with  d2 - d4 . }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally, White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Qc7
12. d5( { This position resembles to the Keres Variation after   }11...Nd7 12.d5 { ( Chapter 2 ). The difference is that we moved our queen to  c7 , with the result that we can't transpose. The queen on  c7  has its plusses and minuses compared to the knight at  d7 . Her majesty helps easily connects the rooks once the bishop at  c8  moves while she supports any ... c5 - c4  advance. } )( { We would have an easy game in case of }12.Be3? Nc4! { when White mostly retreats the bishop to  c1 , after which he has lost two valuable tempi. Besides, we can count ourselves lucky to improve the bad position of our worst-placed piece on  a5 . } )
12. Nc4{ The knight has been redirected from a disadvantageous position (a5) to the more advantageous  b6 -square via  c4 . It now has a strategic view of squares  a4  and  c4  and can be readily repositioned to   d7  if needed. }
13. b3( { The move }13.Nbd2?! { is not played at the highest level, and not without reason. Black is glad to exchange a pair of minor pieces due to his lack of space. }13...Nxd2 14.Bxd2 Nd7= { Transferring the knight to the queenside. The position is 'equalish'. } )
13. Nb6
14. Nbd2
14. c4{ We are bouncing back, trying to prove our point on the knight manoeuvre. After  b2 - b3 , the pawn on  c3  is weakened. }
