3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. O-O
5. Be7
6. Re1
6. b5
7. Bb3
7. d6( { After lengthy consideration, I decided to recommend }7...d6 { . }{ The other main option is }7...O-O { , after which Black can opt for ... d7 - d5  at once. }8.a4!? { is the critical continuation, when Black chooses between }8...Bb7 { , allowing White to shut the bishop out of the game by  d3 , or }8...b4 { , giving up control over the important  c4 -square. } )
8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. O-O
9. h3( 9.h3 { is the most commonly played move for good reason. It prepares the central pawn thrust  10.d4 , preventing any interference from ... Bg4 . } )( { However, }9.d4 { is entirely playable and is called the  Yates Variation . In response, we play }9...Bg4 { , the Bogoljubov Variation! } )
9. Na5{ This is the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez. The knight is temporarily steered to the edge of the board. White can't avoid to lose their best minor piece, the light-squared bishop, so they spend time manoeuvring it from  Bb3  to  c2 . This allows Black to advance their c-pawn, gaining control of the queenside and disrupting White's plans to establish a strong center with  d2 - d4 . }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Qc7
12. Nbd2( { We would have an easy game in case of }12.Be3? Nc4! { when White mostly retreats the bishop to  c1 , after which he has lost two valuable tempi. Besides, we can count ourselves lucky to improve the bad position of our worst-placed piece on  a5 . } )
12. cxd4{ This is the Panov System. It is considered as the 'main line' or the 'creme-de-la-creme' of the Chigorin. Over the years, the Panov System has generally been considered slightly better for White, and there was a brief period when engines suggested Black was much worse. However, with the engines' ever-changing evaluation of chess positions, the Chigorin has become fully playable once again! }
13. cxd4
13. Nc6{ Immediately attacking the  d4 -pawn. When I was a little boy, I faced the Chigorin with the white pieces at the internal league in Leeuwarden against my grey and wise Nestor, Eddie Scholl - who was the Dutch Champion in 1970. As a result, I was so impressed by my opponent, that I totally missed his main idea... I blundered my  d4 -pawn. }
14. Nb3( { Even though White gives up a pawn after }14.Nf1?! Nxd4 15.Nxd4 exd4 { , he will most probably regain it very soon. For instance, }16.Ng3 Re8 17.Bf4 Qb6 18.Ne2 Bb7 { . Nonetheless, Black has levelled the game. } )
14. a5
15. Be3
15. a4
16. Nbd2
16. Nb4{ We sidestep the main path of the Panov now. }( { Thousands of games have been played with }16...Bd7 { . I suffered a painful loss against Michael Adams, where he - like a boa constrictor - inflicted a slow but certain death on me by strangulation. }17...Qb7 18.Qe2 Rfe8 19.Bd3 Rab8 20.dxe5 Nxe5 21.Nxe5 dxe5 22.Bc5! { ⩲ Conquering c5-square }c5 { for his rooks, from where he is shooting on my weak pawns at }e5 { and }b5 { , 1-0 (40),  Adams  (2735) -  Werle  (2591), London 2008. Please see the Model Games section for the analysis of the entire game. } )( { After }16...Nb4 17.Bb1 Bd7 18.a3 { , we provoked a 'hook', which can be used for us to open the b-file and create counterplay. This whole idea of counterplay was not available in the aforementioned game - I advise you to compare the positions arising (with and without  a3 ). } )
17. Bb1
17. Bd7
18. a3{ There it is... the hook!! We will retreat with the knight to follow up with ... b5 - b4 , opening the b-file. }( 18.Nf1 Rfc8! 19.Qe2 a3!⇆ { , ½-½ (33),  Compagnone  (2350) -  Zielinski  (2340), ICCF email 2020. } )
18. Nc6
