8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. O-O
9. h3( 9.h3 { is the most commonly played move for good reason. It prepares the central pawn thrust  10.d4 , preventing any interference from ... Bg4 . } )( { However, }9.d4 { is entirely playable and is called the  Yates Variation . In response, we play }9...Bg4 { , the Bogoljubov Variation! } )
9. Na5{ This is the Chigorin Variation of the Ruy Lopez. The knight is temporarily steered to the edge of the board. White can't avoid to lose their best minor piece, the light-squared bishop, so they spend time manoeuvring it from  Bb3  to  c2 . This allows Black to advance their c-pawn, gaining control of the queenside and disrupting White's plans to establish a strong center with  d2 - d4 . }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ Although we gain a significant amount of space with this move, it's essential to remember that White also has dangerous plans of his own. These often involve the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3 , sometimes followed by  Nf5  or  Nd5 . Additionally, White might aim to exert pressure in the center with the pawn advance  d2 - d4 , potentially expanding further with  d4 - d5 . }
11. d4
11. Qc7
12. Nbd2
12. Be6{ This sideline scores well: 50%. The earliest game in my database dates back to 1940,  Boleslavsky - Panov , where  Panov  lost.    It's interesting to note that the  12...Be6  line is unnamed, but the  12...cxd4  line is named after  Panov . I discovered three early games played by  Zagoriansky , including a win and draw against  Boleslavsky  in 1942 and '43, respectively, and a loss against  Smyslov  in 1943. As a result, I suggest that this line should be named the ' Zagoriansky  Variation'.    These closed positions require clever strategic manoeuvring, which is why I primarily analysed them using Leela. And I can assure you, if you let 'her' run for a while, she foresees a bright future for us. }
13. Nf1( { Black was slightly better after }13.dxe5 dxe5 14.Nf1 ( { In the earliest game played in this system, White's knight interception of }14.Ng5 { did not result in any advantage: }14...Bd7 15.Nf1 ( 15.Qe2 h6 16.Ngf3= { 1-0 (54),  Boleslavsky  -  Panov , Moscow 1940. } )15...h6 16.Nf3 Be6 { Black is OK, due to his active pieces. White cannot use the  d5 -square as it is well-guarded. }17.Ne3 Rad8 18.Qe2 Rfe8 { Prophylaxis against any future  Nd5  or  Nf5 , meanwhile preparing for ... Bf8 . }19.g4 Bf8 20.Kh1 Nh7 21.a4 b4 ( { Another strong idea was }21...c4! { . } )22.Nd5 Bxd5 23.exd5 e4! { Missed by White. }24.Ng1 ( { White cannot take because of }24.Bxe4 Nf6 25.Nd2 Rxd5-+ { The pin becomes fatal. } )24...Rxd5 25.Qxa6 Nf6∓ { 0-1 (40),  Boleslavsky  -  Zagoriansky , Moscow 1942. } )14...Rad8 15.Qe2 Bc4 16.Qe3 Nh5⩱ { 1-0 (40),  Sulskis  (2555) -  Beinoras  (2422) }{ , Vilnius 2009. } )
13. cxd4{ Now that White's knight is on the kingside ( f1 ), this is a good moment to open the c-file and play ... Rac8  next.  Further delaying this capture gives White the option of closing the position by  d4 - d5 . }( { Another playable line is }13...Rfc8 14.Ne3 cxd4 15.cxd4 Nc4 16.Nxc4 Bxc4 { , 0-1 (43),  Saric  (2678) -  Bartel  (2652), Germany 2015. } )
14. cxd4
14. Rac8{ The idea is that we lure the knight to  e3  when we are aiming for the exchange of this knight for our  a5 -knight. }
15. Ne3
15. Nc4{ The best plan in this position. Coping with a lack of space, one ought to exchange a pair of minor pieces to move freely - a pair of knights, in this case. }
16. Nxc4
16. Bxc4{ We got rid of White's strongest piece. }
17. b3
17. Be6
18. Bd3
18. h6{ A novelty. Before deciding on the configuration of pieces, we take control of the  g5 -square (0-1 (18),  Buchhauser  (1817) -  Ziegler  (2228), ICCF email 2014). }
19. Bb2( 19.Be3 d5! { Once again. }20.Rc1 Qa5⇆  )
19. d5{ At the expense of a pawn, Black will grab the initiative. }
20. exd5
20. Nxd5{ The knight is placed wonderfully at  d5 . We can follow up with ... Qa5  & ... Bb4  or ... Nc3 . }
21. Nxe5
21. Bb4{ After the liberating  19...d5 , all of Black's pieces came to live. }
22. Re2
22. Nc3{ Black acquires the pair of bishops and the  d4 -pawn is weak, fully compensating for the loss of a pawn. }
