13. d5( { Black was slightly better after }13.dxe5 dxe5 14.Nf1 ( { In the earliest game played in this system, White's knight interception of }14.Ng5 { did not result in any advantage: }14...Bd7 15.Nf1 ( 15.Qe2 h6 16.Ngf3= { 1-0 (54),  Boleslavsky  -  Panov , Moscow 1940. } )15...h6 16.Nf3 Be6 { Black is OK, due to his active pieces. White cannot use the  d5 -square as it is well-guarded. }17.Ne3 Rad8 18.Qe2 Rfe8 { Prophylaxis against any future  Nd5  or  Nf5 , meanwhile preparing for ... Bf8 . }19.g4 Bf8 20.Kh1 Nh7 21.a4 b4 ( { Another strong idea was }21...c4! { . } )22.Nd5 Bxd5 23.exd5 e4! { Missed by White. }24.Ng1 ( { White cannot take because of }24.Bxe4 Nf6 25.Nd2 Rxd5-+ { The pin becomes fatal. } )24...Rxd5 25.Qxa6 Nf6∓ { 0-1 (40),  Boleslavsky  -  Zagoriansky , Moscow 1942. } )14...Rad8 15.Qe2 Bc4 16.Qe3 Nh5⩱ { 1-0 (40),  Sulskis  (2555) -  Beinoras  (2422) }{ , Vilnius 2009. } )
13. Bd7{ White wins a tempo now that we have to pull our bishop back. On the other hand, in many of these Chigorin variations, Black is forced to reroute the bishop from  b7  to  d7 , losing even more precious time. }
14. Nf1
14. Nc4{ Black grabs the opportunity to improve their knight's position. }
15. Ng3
15. g6{ Keeping the  g3 -knight outside. }
16. b3
16. Nb6{ The knight improved considerably from  a5  to  b6 . }
17. Bg5
17. Rfc8( { Also good was }17...c4!? 18.b4 a5 { Black managed to gain the upper hand on the queenside. }19.a3 Ra6 20.Qd2 Rfa8! { ⇆ }{ Black will invade, keeping White busy on the queenside. } )
18. Qd2
18. a5{ An ambitious plan, aiming for ... c5 - c4  to weaken  c3 . }( { We should not allow White to play }18...c4 19.b4 a5 20.a3 { , keeping the c-file closed. } )
19. Qe2
19. c4
20. bxc4
20. Nxc4{ Black was perfectly fine here. Besides the fact that  c3  is weak, his once-problematic knight is ruling over the board on  c4 . }( 21.Bd3 Na3 22.Rac1 Kg7!? { Aiming to exchange White's best (minor) piece. }23.Qe3 Ng8! { In the meantime we get rid of our worst piece. }24.Bxe7 Nxe7 25.Qg5 Ng8! { Impressive defensive play: the knight covers all the dark squares, so he need not fear  Nf5  or  Nh5 +. }26.Nf5+ Kf8 27.Ne3 Qd8 28.Qxd8+ Rxd8 29.c4 bxc4 30.Nxc4 Nxc4 { Black had slightly preferable chances but was in a peaceful mood. ½-½ (30)  Harikrishna  (2719) -  Kovalev  (2634), Riga 2021. } )
