7. d6( { After lengthy consideration, I decided to recommend }7...d6 { . }{ The other main option is }7...O-O { , after which Black can opt for ... d7 - d5  at once. }8.a4!? { is the critical continuation, when Black chooses between }8...Bb7 { , allowing White to shut the bishop out of the game by  d3 , or }8...b4 { , giving up control over the important  c4 -square. } )
8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. Na5( { This move defines the Accelerated Chigorin. The main line of the Chigorin is }8...O-O { but with }8...Na5 { , we postpone castling in favour of the typical manoeuvre ... Na5  and ... c7 - c5 . }{    Let's make a comparison between the two: after }8...O-O 9.h3 Na5 10.Bc2 c5 11.d4 Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 13.cxd4 Bd7 { , White doesn't have to spend time moving the attacked bishop on  c2  away, after }14.Nf1 Rac8 15.Ne3! { .    Using the move order }{   }8...Na5 9.Bc2 c5 10.h3 Qc7 11.d4 Bd7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 13.cxd4 Rc8 { , we attack the  c2 -bishop one move earlier. } )
9. Bc2
9. c5{ We are following the main line of the Chigorin, with the only difference that we haven't castled yet. }
10. h3{ This move involves an attempt to avoid the Accelerated Chigorin. }
10. Qc7{ In case of short castling, we are back in the main line of the Chigorin. However, deferring this move is expected to yield us something... }
11. d4
11. Bd7{ Again, we are not giving in to the most natural move in this position, i.e., short castling. }
12. d5{ In case of castling short, we would enter the main line of the Chigorin. }
12. Rg8{ We have another ace up our sleeve. As a consequence of White’s  h2 - h3 , we can now attack the ‘hook’ by means of ... g7 - g5 - g4 . }( 12...c4 13.b4!  )
13. Nbd2
13. g5{ Pushing the envelope, exploring new territories! }
14. Nf1
14. g4{ The point: we use the hook on  h3  for our purposes. }
15. hxg4
15. Nxg4{ Mission accomplished: the g-file has been opened and with excellent attacking chances for Black across the g-file. }( { I would like to show you the bright prospects with a sample line: }16.Ng3 O-O-O ( 16...Qd8!? { seems very interesting too. } )17.a4 { White is trying to open up the queenside. We are on a knife edge with our opponent. }17...b4 18.cxb4 cxb4 19.Bd3 Qa7! { ⇆ }{ . }{ Please note that }20.Be3? { does not work because the f-pawn is overloaded. The queen on  a7  is better placed than  b6 , as her majesty could be hit by  a4 - a5  once we move our knight from  a5  to  b7  (and  c5 ). } )
