8. Na5( { This move defines the Accelerated Chigorin. The main line of the Chigorin is }8...O-O { but with }8...Na5 { , we postpone castling in favour of the typical manoeuvre ... Na5  and ... c7 - c5 . }{    Let's make a comparison between the two: after }8...O-O 9.h3 Na5 10.Bc2 c5 11.d4 Qc7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 13.cxd4 Bd7 { , White doesn't have to spend time moving the attacked bishop on  c2  away, after }14.Nf1 Rac8 15.Ne3! { .    Using the move order }{   }8...Na5 9.Bc2 c5 10.h3 Qc7 11.d4 Bd7 12.Nbd2 cxd4 13.cxd4 Rc8 { , we attack the  c2 -bishop one move earlier. } )
9. Bc2
9. c5{ We are following the main line of the Chigorin, with the only difference that we haven't castled yet. }
10. d4
10. cxd4( 10...Qc7 { , with the idea to protect the  e5 -pawn, is the main line of the Chigorin. In the Accelerated Chigorin, Black tries to do without the queen's move. } )
11. cxd4
11. Bg4{ We are at crossroads here, splitting up the Accelerated Chigorin in two topical lines. White is still looking for an advantage in this new and offbeat variation. }
12. Nbd2
12. Nc6{ Enhancing the pressure even further on the central  d4 -square. }
13. h3
13. Bh5{ Naturally, we can't give up on our best minor piece without a fight. Moreover, we prefer to maintain the pin. }
14. g4{ Currently, this is the most topical line of the Accelerated Chigorin. }
14. Nxg4{ In exchange for a piece, we get a strong attack on the white king and... two pawns. }
15. hxg4
15. Bxg4{ On top of this, White is not yet coordinated and should try very hard to redeploy his troops ASAP. }
16. Nb3
16. O-O{ By castling, we are not merely hiding our own king. At the same time, the  f8 -rook is catapulted towards the enemy king by means of ... f7 - f5 . }
17. d5
17. Nb4{ After this move, White doesn't have time to consolidate due to the positional threat of ... Nxc2  and ... Bxf3 . }
18. Bb1
18. f5{ The key part of Black's strategy: the files must be opened in order to grant access to Black's artillery. }
19. a3
19. Qe8{ Practically, White is in dire straits and he should watch his steps carefully. }
20. exf5( { The position of the French GM Edouard went quickly downhill after }20.axb4 Qh5! 21.Nbd2 { We shouldn't be wavering here since White is planning on consolidating his position across the third rank by  Ra3 ! }21...Bh3 22.Nf1 f4!∓ { , 0-1 (34),  Edouard  (2640) -  Santos Latasa  (2600), Los Cancajos 2020. } )
20. Qh5{ Black's attack gets real shape. }
21. Be4( { Not much better was }21.Nbd2 { due to }21...Bg5! { → }{ . } )
21. Rxf5{ The black pieces are unstoppable. }
22. Nbd2( { Taking the exchange with }22.Bxf5 Qxf5 23.Nbd2 { would merely accelerate our plans after }23...Nc2-+ { . } )
22. Nd3( { The knight takes center stage, after which White can't hold things together: }23.Bxd3 Rxf3 24.Be2 { Surprisingly, two games have been played here, at the top level. The attack on the king is already so promising, that there are more paths to Rome here. }24...Qg6! { Sadly enough, here White cannot even take on  f3 . White position collapses as a result of the barefooted king on the g-file. }( { Tempting and also winning was }24...Rh3! 25.Bxg4 Rh1+ 26.Kg2 Qh2+ 27.Kf3 Qf4+ { . Now that Black is winning a piece back, the material balance is restored while the attack proceeds. }28.Ke2 Qxg4+ 29.f3 Rh2+ 30.Kd3 Qd4+ 31.Kc2 Bg5! { The knight on  d2  is pinned and White cannot disentangle. 0-1 (50)  Navara  (2734) -  Predke  (2632), Riga 2019. } )25.Nf1 Bf5+ { Maghsoodloo was completely getting crushed. }26.Kh1 ( { Blocking the g-file with }26.Ng3 { won't bring White any relief. }26...Rxg3+ 27.fxg3 Qxg3+ 28.Kh1 Be4+-+  )26...Rxf2 { There is no way to stop the black pieces. }27.Bf3 Bc2 28.Bh5 Qg2# { , 0-1 (28)  Maghsoodloo  (2701) -  Santos Latasa  (2635), Ciudad Real 2021. } )
