1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. O-O
5. Be7
6. Re1
6. b5
7. Bb3
7. d6( { After lengthy consideration, I decided to recommend }7...d6 { . }{ The other main option is }7...O-O { , after which Black can opt for ... d7 - d5  at once. }8.a4!? { is the critical continuation, when Black chooses between }8...Bb7 { , allowing White to shut the bishop out of the game by  d3 , or }8...b4 { , giving up control over the important  c4 -square. } )
8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. O-O
9. d4{ The Bogoljubow Variation takes its name from the game  Capablanca - Bogoljubow  and  Yates - Bogoljubow , London 1922 and  Lasker - Bogoljubow , Moravská Ostrava 1923. }( 9.d4!? { appears to be an inaccuracy, refraining }{ from  h2 - h3  and allowing ... Bc8 - g4 , but emerged as a serious alternative to the  main line  }9.h3 { in the Ruy Lopez. } )
9. Bg4{ Pinning the knight. }
10. h3
10. Bxf3{ White's central pawn is insufficiently protected. }
11. gxf3
11. Na5{ Chasing the bishop from the long diagonal and aiming for ... exd4  followed by ... c5 . }
12. Bc2
12. Nh5{ With the aim to settle on  f4 . }
13. f4{ Strategically speaking, the only move. }
13. Nxf4
14. Bxf4
14. exf4{ It requires time for our opponent to win back the  f4 -pawn. We are using that time to weaken our opponent on  d4 . }
15. Qg4
15. c5{ Black is already much better. White has no good defense against ... Nc6  and ... Bf6 . }( 16.Nd2 cxd4 17.cxd4 Rc8 18.Bd3 Bf6 19.Nf3 Nc6 { was 0-1  Neumann  -  Negyesy , Czechoslovakia 1962. } )
