10. exd4{ The main line as we all know it. As seen before, we are handing over the center to White, but finding ways to seek active play on the queenside. Nonetheless, due to recent theoretical developments (amongst others,  Giri  -  Carlsen ), White is having a slight and unpleasant pull here. }
11. cxd4
11. Na5{ Hitting the bishop on  b3 , while getting ready for the c-pawn push. }
12. Bc2{ Of course, White is keeping his strongest minor piece, you'd say. Nonetheless, it transpires that in the quest for an opening advantage, White assumed that he could do without... }( { ➢ }12.h3!? { I was surprised to see so many games continued  12.h3 . White gives up his strongest minor piece without getting something in return; at least that was my first thought here. }12...Nxb3 13.axb3 Bh5 ( 13...Bd7 { was tried by  Magnus Carlsen  in an internet game, so how dare I suggest deviating? Nonetheless,  Kamsky  demonstrated how White should play against  10...exd4  and  10...Bh5  is the way to go for Black. }14.Bd2 Qc8 { . }{ 1-0 (48),  Aronian  (2781) -  Carlsen  (2847), chess24.com 2021. }15.b4!? { Fixing  a6  and  c7 , when White is slightly better. } )14.Nbd2 Qd7! { The idea is to prepare for ... c7 - c5  and to make  g4  less attractive. }( { It's unclear if Black fully equalizes with }14...d5 15.e5 Ne4 { , }{ with complications in  Shirov  (2664) -  Sargissian , (2690), 1-0 (46), Douglas 2019. } )15.Qc2 ( 15.g4? Bg6! 16.Bf4 Rfe8∓ { and Black is very flexible while he has many targets in sight ( g4 ,  e4 ). Possible continuations are ... c5 , ... Bf8 , or ... h5 . } )15...Rfc8! { Aiming to hit the center and queen by means of ... c7 - c5 . }16.b4 h6! { The idea behind this small move is to put the bishop on the long  h7 - b1  diagonal. }17.Nh4 ( { For instance, after }17.Rac1 { , }{ Black can move the bishop to }17...Bg6 { without being harassed by the next knight move. }18.Nh4 Bh7 { . } )17...d5! { Collateral damage for White is that the pawn on  b4  is hanging. }18.e5 Nh7 19.Ndf3 ( { White is losing a pawn, after }19.Nf5 Bxb4⩱ { . } )19...Bxf3 20.Nxf3 Bxb4 21.Bd2 c5! { Black owned a comfortable advantage due to his extra pawn. Next, his knight will be moved to  f8  and eventually  g6  or  e6 . ½-½ (32),  Sutovsky  (2687) -  Kamsky  (2744), Amsterdam 2012. } )( { ➢ }12.Nbd2 { was tried once by the Dutch young star  Jorden van Foreest  in an internet game. I don't think that White can achieve an opening advantage without his light-squared bishop. }12...Nxb3 ( { Not all the top players take the bishop on  b3  blindly: }12...c5 13.Bc2 cxd4 14.Bxd4 Nc6 15.Be3 d5 ( 15...Rc8⇆ { 0-1 (27),  J. van Foreest  (2698) -  Artemiev , (2704), chess24.com 2021. } )16.h3 Bh5 17.Rc1 Rc8⇆ { ½-½ (60),  Fedoseev  (2678) -  Kovalev , (2648), lichess.org 2020. } )13.axb3 ( { The queen has nothing to do on  b3 , for example, }13.Qxb3 c5⩱ { . } )13...c5 ( { We have a choice, although I don't see the point to give White the center after }13...d5 14.e5 Ne4 15.Qc2⩲ { . } )14.Qc2 Nd7 { , }{ this regrouping of pieces is giving Black the better chances. The bishop is deployed on  f6 , whereas the knight is waiting for its turn before it moves to  e5  or  c5 . }15.e5 cxd4! {  Carlsen  opens the position by the mass exchanges, keeping the bishop pair. Moreover, White is suffering from two weak doubled b-pawns. }16.Bxd4 dxe5 17.Nxe5 Nxe5 18.Bxe5 Re8⩱ { . }{ 0-1 (84),  Fedoseev  (2718) -  Carlsen  (2837), Riyadh 2017. } )
12. Nc4{ Why not this move? Chasing the  e3 -bishop, and once chased by  b2 - b3 , we improve the knight's position from  a5  (via  c4 ) to  b6 . }( { One of the cornerstones of White's strategy emerges in the next main line: }12...c5 13.h3 Bh5 ( 13...Bxf3 14.Qxf3 cxd4 15.Bxd4 Rc8 16.Qd1 Nc6 17.Nc3 Nxd4 18.Qxd4⩲ { . }{ ½-½ (60),  Deac  (2639) -  Ivanchuk  (2678), Europe Echecs 2021. } )14.g4!? { Black cannot yet make use of the weakening of the white kingside. }14...Bg6 { , }{ we have no choice but to retreat. }15.Nbd2 Re8 16.d5! { Closing the center, and closing in on the bishop on  g6 . }16...Nd7 17.Nh2! { So straightforward this plan of  f2 - f4 - f5  (catching the  g6 -bishop) but it's hard for Black to stop this expansion. White has a slight pull. 1-0 (42),  Pavlov  (2485) -  Rydstrom  (2322), Uppsala 2019. }17...h6 18.f4 Bh7 19.b3 Bf6 20.Rc1 c4 21.Nhf3⩲ { . } )
13. Bc1
13. d5( { This is the critical position I was referring to at the 10th move. With the bishop on  h5 , the tactics don't work for White after }14.e5 Ne4 15.b3 Nb6 16.Nbd2 Nc3 17.Bxh7+ { . } )( 13...c5!? { Better than  13...d5 , but not equalizing. }14.b3 Nb6 ( 14...Na5 { , }{ Capablanca went wrong here, as White can obtain a large advantage with  15.d5 , when the knight is committing an offside. }15.d5! ( { ( }15.Bb2?! { was 1-0  Capablanca  -  Bogoljubow  London 1922). }15...cxd4!  ) )15.Nbd2 Rc8 16.Bb2! { and the theoretical discussion is ongoing. I couldn't find equality here yet. 1-0  Deac  (2683) -  Nasuta  (2512), chess.com 2022. } )
14. e5
14. Ne4{ Due to a finesse, this foothold is not as solid as it appears. }
15. b3( { Another less popular line is }15.Nc3 Nxc3 16.bxc3 Bh5! { Black aims to exchange the light-squared bishop. }17.Bf5 Bg6 18.g4 a5⇆ { .    And if   }18.Bxg6 fxg6!? { , }{ opening the f-file for the rook. Play could proceed with }19.Nd2 Nb6 20.Qg4 Na4 { , }{ with pressure against the pawn on  c3 . }21.Re3 Qc8 22.e6 c5 23.Nf3 cxd4 24.cxd4 Nc3⇆ { , }{ 0-1 (63),  Rimkus  (2279) -  Campian  (2320), ICCF email 2007. } )
15. Nb6
