8. c3{ This move marks the beginning of the traditional Ruy Lopez setup, from which various lines emerge, including the Chigorin variation. }( { It's worth noting that }8.a4 { is not effective in this position because of }8...Bd7! { , as demonstrated in the  8th Move Alternatives  chapter. } )
8. O-O
9. d4{ The Bogoljubow Variation takes its name from the game  Capablanca - Bogoljubow  and  Yates - Bogoljubow , London 1922 and  Lasker - Bogoljubow , Moravská Ostrava 1923. }( 9.d4!? { appears to be an inaccuracy, refraining }{ from  h2 - h3  and allowing ... Bc8 - g4 , but emerged as a serious alternative to the  main line  }9.h3 { in the Ruy Lopez. } )
9. Bg4{ Pinning the knight. }
10. Be3
10. Bh5( { This mysterious move serves different purposes. One can be witnessed in the line arising after }11.h3 exd4 12.cxd4 Na5 13.Bc2 Nc4 14.Bc1 d5 15.e5 Ne4 { , where the bishop is less vulnerable }{ on  h5  than on  g4 . Sometimes we can use the  g4 -square for our knight and White doesn't have  g2 - g4  at his disposal, which can prove useful as seen in the  informational line   10...exd4 . }( { Last but not least, after }11.Nbd2 { , we handily make use of the break in the center }{ by ... d6 - d5 . }{ Also, note that   }10...Nxe4? { runs into }11.Bd5 { , attacking both knights. } ) )
11. a4{ This can be considered a sideline, but it's not without venom. }
11. Na5{ White has to make an important decision: will he maintain his bishop on its dominant position across the  a2 - g8  diagonal, or retreat to  c2 ? }
12. Ba2{ Obviously, an attacking and creative player like  Sutovsky  prefers the active solution! 1-0 (26),  Sutovsky  (2626) -  Damaso  (2451), Jerusalem 2015. }
12. exd4{ Deviating from the aforementioned  Sutovsky  game; we strike in the center. }
13. cxd4{ White is this time not so keen to take back with the pawn. }
13. d5{ Black is poised to hit the center now that White is not yet fully developed. }
14. e5
14. Ne4{ With ... Nc4  coming, only Black can claim a (small) advantage here. }
