11. d5{ And so Black waited his turn to strike in the center. Tactically, after White's last move with the knight on  d2 , this is working now. This relatively new line is still in progress and White is still searching for ways to an opening advantage. }( { After }11...Na5 12.dxe5! dxe5 13.h3 { , strangely enough, White can trade his strong bishop in the quest for an advantage. }13...Nxb3 14.Qxb3 Bd6 15.c4!⩲ { . } )
12. Bg5
12. exd4{ Not fearing  exd5  since we can take on  c3  in between. }
13. exd5( 13.cxd4? { is simply bad due to }13...Nxd4 { . } )
13. dxc3( { We are hitting the  d2 -knight. }13...Nxd5? { is definitely something to avoid, as }14.Bxd5 { wins a piece. } )
14. dxc6
14. cxd2
15. Qxd2( { In case of }15.Bxd2 { , we have a pleasant choice between }15...Re8 { , }15...Bxf3 { (the  d2 -bishop is hanging), }{ or }15...Bd6 { . } )
15. Qxd2{ If White takes back with the bishop, we take the opportunity to activate the bishop to  b4 . }
16. Bxd2
16. Bd6{ As steady as a rock on  d6 . }
17. Nh4
17. Rfe8{ We can consider this a strong novelty since Black can move the bishop to  e5  now. }( { ➢ }17...Rad8?! 18.h3!+= { , }{ taking the  g4 -square away from our pieces. Moreover,  Nh4 - f5  is getting a real nuisance. }( 18.Bc3?! { The former World Champion missed his chance. }18...Bg4!= { , ½-½ (36),  Ponomariov  (2712) -  Svidler  (2756), Khanty-Mansiysk 2017. } )18...Rfe8 19.Ba5⩲ { and White has a }{ slight pull here.  Nf5  is coming, enhancing the pressure on  d6  and  c7 . } )( { ➢ }17...Bg6?! { was played by the Polish GM  Bartel , just giving up his bishop pair. I consider this a panicking move, which is not absolutely necessary. }18.Nxg6 hxg6⩲ { . ½-½ (30),  Smirnov  (2482) -  Bartel  (2646), Baku 2016. } )
18. Nf5
18. Be5{ We have the better position here. I feel like the  c6 -pawn is rather weak than strong, whereas we are about to chase the  f5 -knight away with ... Bh5 - g6 . }
