10. Bh5( { This mysterious move serves different purposes. One can be witnessed in the line arising after }11.h3 exd4 12.cxd4 Na5 13.Bc2 Nc4 14.Bc1 d5 15.e5 Ne4 { , where the bishop is less vulnerable }{ on  h5  than on  g4 . Sometimes we can use the  g4 -square for our knight and White doesn't have  g2 - g4  at his disposal, which can prove useful as seen in the  informational line   10...exd4 . }( { Last but not least, after }11.Nbd2 { , we handily make use of the break in the center }{ by ... d6 - d5 . }{ Also, note that   }10...Nxe4? { runs into }11.Bd5 { , attacking both knights. } ) )
11. h3
11. exd4( { All in line with the main line after   }10...exd4 11.cxd4 Na5 { and }12.Bc2 c5 { (please see the  informational line  for more details). } )
12. cxd4
12. Na5{ Following the same plan as in the (old) main line. Chasing the  b3 -bishop and pushing the c-pawn. }
13. Bc2
13. Nc4{ It seems like we reached a transposition of moves in comparance with the (old) main line. }
14. Bc1
14. d5{ And here, the difference of having  h3  and ... Bh5  included will come to the surface in the next line: }
15. e5
15. Ne4{ Of crucial importance is that White cannot play  b3  and  Nbd2 , neutralizing our strong knight on  e4 , as will be pointed out rapidly. }
16. Nc3
16. Nxc3
17. bxc3
17. a5{ Black is planning to create some counterplay with ... b5 - b4  and has the extra option of deploying the rook across the 6th rank. }
18. g4{ I think that White is not ready for this risky plan, throwing his pawns forward. }
18. Bg6
19. Bf5
19. b4{ Providing us with the so-desired counterplay. }
20. cxb4
20. axb4
21. Qd3
21. Ra6{ White can barely move here. I don't see any follow-up. }
