4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. O-O
5. Be7
6. d3{ The Marshall players are grinding their teeth on this move, as it is directed against a quick ... d7 - d5 . On top of that, it is calling for immediate action for Black, since White wants to win a pawn by  Bxc6  and  Nxe5 .    The drawback of playing  6.d3  is that White abandons their ambitions of swiftly establishing a formidable center through moves like  Re1 ,  c3 , and  d4 . }
6. b5( 6...O-O? { is not to be recommended: }7.Bxc6 dxc6 8.Nxe5 { just wins a pawn for White. } )
7. Bb3
7. d6
8. a4{ Currently, Black is poised to encounter  8.a4  with  8...Bd7 . }
8. Bd7{ Following in the footsteps of GM  Gustafsson 's  Lifetime Repertoires:   1.e4 e5  (2019):     'Connecting the queen on  d8  and the rook on  a8 , thereby parrying the threat of  axb5 . This is fairly established as the best move here - sorry to  8...b4  fans. The bishop looks a bit passive, but it still has greater prospects on this diagonal than on  b7 .'     I couldn't agree more! The bishop move is very flexible and so is the pawn structure. }
9. Bd2{ ' As usual, the idea is to stop ... Na5 , but in this iteration with a pawn on  a4  and bishop on  d7 , ... b5 - b4  will often be a useful resource for Black, locking up the knight on  b1 . ' }
9. O-O{ As  Gustafsson  states:    ' A tad more precise to start with this than with ... b4 , as  axb5  is not a threat yet. '    This is also more to my taste, holding our cards close to the chest. }
10. h3
10. b4{ Good timing, since  10.h3  is not too challenging for us. }
11. a5
11. Rb8{ This topical line has recently been played often on a high level. }
12. c3
12. bxc3
13. bxc3
13. Be6{ I picked this straightforward approach from a recent Shirov game in which White couldn't claim any advantage throughout the entire game. }
14. Bxe6
14. fxe6
15. Be3
15. d5{ Putting some pressure on White's center. More importantly, Black takes space and will be able to move his bishop to  d6 . }
16. Nbd2
16. Qd7{ Easy moves to play. }
17. Qc2
17. Bd6( { The position is drawish: White has a weak pawn at  a5  while Black has doubled pawns.    Please click through the next moves to see how easily Shirov managed to hold the balance: }18.Rfb1 h6 19.d4 exd4 20.Rxb8 Rxb8 21.Nxd4 Bc5 22.exd5 Nxd5 23.Nxc6 Qxc6 24.Bxc5 Qxc5 25.Ne4 Qc4 26.Rd1 e5 27.Qd3 Qxd3 28.Rxd3 Nf6 29.Nxf6+ gxf6 30.Rd7 Rb5= { and after a couple of moves, the players agreed to a draw in ½-½ (35),  Grandelius  (2656) -  Shirov , (2693) Malmo 2022. } )
