6. b5( 6...O-O? { is not to be recommended: }7.Bxc6 dxc6 8.Nxe5 { just wins a pawn for White. } )
7. Bb3
7. d6
8. c3{ Making place for the bishop retreat to  c2 , in case of ... Na5 . }
8. O-O{ The main line. We will encounter a lot of transpositions of moves. In the bigger deal of the games, White will not rush but positionally improve his  b1 -knight in the typical Ruy Lopez knight manoeuvre  b1 - d2 - f1 - g3 / e3  (with the footprint of Fischer), play  h3  and then think about  d3 - d4 . In most of the lines, we follow the same plan of ... Na5 , ... c5  and ... Nc6 , with the footprint of Chigorin! }
9. h3( 9.Nbd2 Na5 10.Bc2 c5 11.d4 Qc7 { . This position leads to the main line of the Chigorin, with the only difference being that White lost a tempo by playing  d3 - d4 . } )( 9.a4 Bd7 { would transpose to the   8.a4  chapter . } )
9. Na5{ There it is: the Chigorin approach! }
10. Bc2
10. c5{ And again, the Chigorin approach! }
11. Re1( 11.Nbd2 Nc6 12.Re1 { is a transposition. } )
11. Nc6
12. d4{ A very tricky move by the Dutch star  Jorden van Foreest . The idea behind is that after multiple exchanges on  d4 , the  c3 -square will be available for the knight. }
12. exd4{ A bit of surprising strategy, giving up on our central pawn. }( { Artemiev fell for Jorden's opening trickery with }12...cxd4 13.cxd4! { . The knight is jumping to secure its place on  c3 ! }13...Nxd4 14.Nxd4 exd4 15.Qxd4 { Since the queen can't be easily chased away, Black cannot free himself with ... d6 - d5 . }15...Be6 16.Nc3!⩲ { As said before, Black can't liberate himself with ... d6 - d5  and White managed to move his knight to  c3 . ½-½ (31),  J. van Foreest  (2701) -  Artemiev  (2709), Tornelo 2021. For instance, the tactics don't work for Black in case of }16...d5? 17.exd5 Nxd5 18.Nxd5 Bxd5 19.Rxe7! { when  d5  is hanging. }19...Qxe7 20.Qxd5 Qe1+ 21.Kh2 Rad8 22.Qf5 g6 23.Qf6+-  )
13. cxd4
13. Nb4{ White cannot maintain his strong bishop, since after  Bb3  Black can play ... c5 - c4 . }
14. Nc3
14. Nxc2
15. Qxc2
15. Bb7{ Black had decent play in  Janev  (2472) -  Baramidze  (2583), ½-½ (19), Plovdiv 2008. }
