8. Bd2{ Contrary to the previous moves witnessed,  8.Bd2  maintains the  b3 -bishop. White is aiming for impeding Black's most trusted scheme consisting of  Na5  followed by  c5 . }( { White should at least aim to maintain their light-squared bishop; the moves  8.h3  and  8.Nc3  should be dissuaded: }8.Nc3 Na5⩱ { , } )( 8.h3?! { An overcautious move, as White - in contrast to the main line - will not follow up with  c3  and  d4 . }8...Na5! { Simply catching White's best minor piece. }9.Nc3 O-O 10.Bd2 Nxb3 ( 10...c5?! { gives away the advantage. }11.Nd5 Nxb3 12.Nxe7+ Qxe7 13.axb3= { , 0-1 (41),  Fedoseev  (2701) -  Kollars  (2637), chess.com 2022. } )11.axb3 Bb7⩱ { We didn't have to work hard for the bishop pair. } )
8. Bg4{ Moving twice with the same piece, but forcing White to play  c2 - c3  which entails that  Bd2  was a useless move. }( { The main line goes }8...O-O 9.h3 { but I couldn't find a clear way to fully equalise. } )
9. c3
9. Na5{ This 'impulsive' knight move is one of the key ideas in the Chigorin, intending to throw the c-pawn forward. }( 9...Bh5 { was played by Esipenko but it is an inaccurate move as White can get the tiny better chances in case of }10.Bc1! ( 10.Re1 Na5 11.Bc2 c5 12.h3 { is similar to what happened in the game, ½-½ (36),  Sethuraman  (2641) -  Svane  (2608), Moscow 2020. } )10...O-O 11.Nbd2 Na5 12.Bc2 c5 13.Re1!⩲ { By postponing  h3 , White makes work of the quick transfer of the knight from the queen- to the kingside. } )
10. Bc2
10. c5
11. h3{ As seen in the Smart Ruy Lopez Chessable course, this move ought to be played rather quickly by White so that Black has to make up his mind if he steps from the  c8 - h3  or  h5 - d1  diagonal. }
11. Bh5
12. Re1
12. O-O
13. Bc1{ I couldn't believe my eyes when I first looked at the board, then in the database watching the number of games being played with  13.Bc1 ! }
13. Qc7{ Black goes straight for his goal and doesn't wait like a docile lamb on white carrying out his so beloved  Nb1 - d2 - f1 - g3  manoeuvre, when our bishop is a tad misplaced on  g6 . }
14. Nbd2
14. Rad8{ Trying to steamroll White with ... d6 - d5  and eventually (if White allows it) with ... c5 - c4 . }
15. Qe2
15. Rfe8{ Placing the rook on the same file as the queen. }
16. g4
16. Bg6
17. a4
17. b4{ Naturally keeping the a-file closed. }
18. cxb4
18. cxb4{ Fortunately for us, White cannot easily redeploy his bishop at the  a2 - g8  diagonal. }
19. Nb3
19. Rc8( { Black easily obtained an equal position after }20.Bd1 d5 21.Nh4 dxe4 22.dxe4 Nc4 23.Nxg6 hxg6 24.Nd2 Nxd2= { ½-½ (24),  Dessaules  (2394) -  Rets  (2370), ICCF email 2021. } )( { Or }19...Nb7!?Ν { With the aim to stop the  c2 -bishop to reach too easily the  a2 - g8  diagonal. }20.Be3 d5 21.Rac1 d4 22.Bb1 Qd6 { with an unclear position. } )
