6. Qe2( { In the Worrall Attack, White replaces }6.Re1 { for }6.Qe2 { . The idea is that the queen protects the e-pawn, leaving the }{ rook free to move to  d1  to support the advance of the d-pawn. } )
6. b5{ Never forget that once the  e4 -pawn is protected, we should take notice of the threat  Bxc6  and  Nxe5 . }
7. Bb3
7. O-O
8. a4( { The insipid move }8.d3 { in conjunction }{ with  Qe2 , leads to a  transposition , after }8...d6 9.a4 b4 10.a5 Rb8 { . } )
8. b4{ The best continuation, as it grabs space and keeps the a-file closed. }
9. d3
9. d6{ In case White denies to resume with  a4 - a5 , he leaves Black with several options to obtain an equal position. }
10. h3
10. Na5
11. Ba2
11. c5
12. Nbd2
12. Rb8{ A useful move since Black can oppose  c2 - c3  by ... b4 - b3 ! Black will resume by moving the bishop to  e6  and the queen to  d7 , leading to an equal position. }
