2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. O-O
5. Be7
6. Bxc6{ This move may strike you as a peculiar move: White lost a tempo by having played  Ba4  and only then  Bxc6 . Nonetheless, there is a sophisticated idea behind White's moves: in the meantime, Black has played ... Nf6  and the knight obstructs a quick ... f7 - f6  (to protect the  e5 -pawn) and the bishop is a tad misplaced on  e7 . }
6. dxc6{ Obviously, we take back with the d-pawn. The  c8 -bishop gets more scope. }
7. Qe1{ The idea behind this mysterious queen move is that White is attempting to play  d2 - d4  (without losing a tempo by  d2 - d3 ). }
7. Be6( { During the last round of the Dutch Championships in 2005, I didn't react well against the nasty little opening variation of my opponent: }7...Nd7 8.b3!? O-O 9.Bb2 f6 10.d4 exd4 11.Nxd4 Nc5 12.Nd2 Qe8 13.Qe3⩲ { . This game is annotated in the  Smart Ruy Lopez - The Exchange Variation, Part 1 , 1-0 (36)  Stellwagen  (2533) -  Werle  (2514), Leeuwarden 2005. } )
8. Nxe5{ A common theme in the (delayed) exchange variation of the Ruy-Lopez: White takes the pawn on  e5  after which the position takes a sharp turn. }( 8.d3 { is just too slow. }8...Nd7 9.Nbd2 f6 10.b3 c5∓ { . } )
8. Qd4{ With a double attack on the knight and pawn. }
9. Nf3
9. Qxe4{ Regaining the pawn with interest. }
10. Qxe4
10. Nxe4{ Black has nothing to fear in this endgame. }
11. Re1
11. Nd6( { Please have a look at the following Model Game on how to convert your bishop pair advantage in the ending: }12.Nd4 Bg4 13.h3 Bh5 14.Nc3 Kd7 15.d3 Rae8 16.Bd2 b6 17.Ne4 Bg6 18.Bc3 f6 19.Ng3 h5 20.Re2 h4 21.Nf1 Bh5 22.Ree1 c5! { The knights lack strongholds and are slowly being pushed away. Against }23.Nb3 { , }23...Nb5! { is a strong reply }{ . 0-1 (59),  Manolov  (2340) -  Sokolov  (2625), Elenite 1992. } )
