4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. O-O
5. Be7
6. Bxc6{ This move may strike you as a peculiar move: White lost a tempo by having played  Ba4  and only then  Bxc6 . Nonetheless, there is a sophisticated idea behind White's moves: in the meantime, Black has played ... Nf6  and the knight obstructs a quick ... f7 - f6  (to protect the  e5 -pawn) and the bishop is a tad misplaced on  e7 . }
6. dxc6{ Obviously, we take back with the d-pawn. The  c8 -bishop gets more scope. }
7. d3
7. Nd7{ The  e5 -pawn needed cover. We have plenty of choices, but I picked the main line as it seems the most solid to me. }( { A fashionable line is }7...Bd6!? { . It was played in the game  McShane - Svane  (Dortmund, July 2022). Black also loses a tempo with his bishop (... Bf8 - e7 - d6  versus  Bb5 - a4 -x c6 ). }8.Nbd2 Be6 { Stopping  Nc4 . }9.b3 Nd7 { Fortifying the  e5 -pawn. }10.Bb2 Qe7 { Preparing to castle queenside. }11.d4 f6!⩱ { Black successfully dealt with the pressure on  e5 . } )
8. b3
8. O-O
9. Bb2
9. f6{ Blocking the  b2 -bishop's diagonal with a pawn chain. }
10. Nbd2
