6. Bxc6{ This move may strike you as a peculiar move: White lost a tempo by having played  Ba4  and only then  Bxc6 . Nonetheless, there is a sophisticated idea behind White's moves: in the meantime, Black has played ... Nf6  and the knight obstructs a quick ... f7 - f6  (to protect the  e5 -pawn) and the bishop is a tad misplaced on  e7 . }
6. dxc6{ Obviously, we take back with the d-pawn. The  c8 -bishop gets more scope. }
7. d3
7. Nd7{ The  e5 -pawn needed cover. We have plenty of choices, but I picked the main line as it seems the most solid to me. }( { A fashionable line is }7...Bd6!? { . It was played in the game  McShane - Svane  (Dortmund, July 2022). Black also loses a tempo with his bishop (... Bf8 - e7 - d6  versus  Bb5 - a4 -x c6 ). }8.Nbd2 Be6 { Stopping  Nc4 . }9.b3 Nd7 { Fortifying the  e5 -pawn. }10.Bb2 Qe7 { Preparing to castle queenside. }11.d4 f6!⩱ { Black successfully dealt with the pressure on  e5 . } )
8. Nbd2
8. O-O{ We have time to castle, letting White execute his knight hopping, while we improve our own pieces. }
9. Nc4
9. f6{ Finally, our  e5 -pawn is fully protected. As a result, we can improve our knight. }
10. Nh4
10. g6( { It is better to obstruct White's plan of using the  f5 -square for their knights than to allow  11.Nf5  by  10...Nc5 : }10...Nc5 11.Nf5 { One way or another, Black has to say farewell to his pair of bishops. }11...Bxf5 12.exf5 { White has firm control over the light squares. }12...Qd7 13.Qf3 Qd5 14.Qg4 Rfe8 { The dark-squared bishop is a problem child as it is blocked by its pawns. }15.Re1 b5 16.Nd2⩲ { White had a stable positional advantage in  Shevchenko  (2655) -  Santos Latasa  (2639), ½-½ (43), Warsaw 2021. } )
11. Qg4( { The move }11.Nf3 { appeared plenty of times in practice. Nonetheless, we don't have to take it very seriously as the knight seems to be uncertain of where to go/stay, losing two valuable tempi on the road. After }11...Nc5 { , Black is already somewhat better. } )( 11.f4 { is a logical but bad continuation. }11...exf4 12.Bxf4 f5!∓ { Suddenly, Black takes over. The knight is hanging and ... fxe4  is a positional threat. } )
11. Kh8{ Not fearing ghosts. }
12. f4
12. exf4{ The prophylactic  11...Kh8  makes it possible to fork White with ... g6 - g5 . }( 12...Rg8? { is too docile, especially when Adhiban is playing the black pieces. }13.Nf3 Nc5 14.Qg3 exf4 15.Bxf4 Ne6 16.Bd2± { ½-½ (27),  Simonian  (2468) -  Eljanov  (2712), Alushta 2011. } )
13. Nxg6+
13. hxg6{ Again we are on knife's edge, but we can rely on the same defensive resource. }
14. Qxg6
14. Qe8
15. Qh6+
15. Kg8{ White is out of checks and we are set for ... Qe8 - f7 - h7 . }
16. Rxf4( { A better attempt would be }16.Bxf4 { but Black is still a piece up in case of }16...Ne5! 17.Nxe5 fxe5 18.Bxe5?? Bc5+!! 19.d4 Qxe5∓ { . } )
16. Ne5{ The bishop begins to interfere with the king's position, making the  g4 -square inaccessible to the rook. }
17. Rh4
17. Qg6( { White can give two lousy checks }{ ( }18.Qh8+ Kf7 19.Rh7+ { ) but ought to resign }{ subsequently as the king can hide on  e8  }{ ( }19...Ke8 { ) }{ . } )
