[White "A16) RL – Anderssen Variation 5.d3"]
[Black "Anderssen Variation 5.d3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. d3{ The so-called Anderssen Variation should be taken seriously, not in the last place because it's played by all the world-class players (from time to time), such as Carlsen, Caruana, Anand, Rapport and so on. On the other hand, I don't think we should be too afraid of this line since we have not yet committed our bishop to  e7 , and can nail it on the more active  c5 -square! }
5. b5{ Please take into account the threat of  Bxc6  and  Nxe5 . We are stopping this once and for all with  5...b5 . }
6. Bb3
6. Bc5( { Since White committed to the somewhat passive  5.d3 , this active bishop move is very to the point. White now has a broad choice of moves, like }7.Bg5 { , }7.c3 { , }7.a4 { , }7.O-O { and }7.Nc3 { . } )
7. Bg5( { At this point, there are many ways to reach the  7.O-O  variation. Let's cover those move orders here:      }7.h3 d6 8.c3 O-O 9.O-O { ,      }7.h3 d6 8.O-O O-O 9.c3 { ,      }7.c3 d6 8.O-O O-O 9.h3 { . } )
7. h6{ The idea consisting of chasing the bishop by  h6  and  g5 , is gaining in strength now that Black hasn't castled yet. Any sacrifices on  g5  shouldn't be feared anyway. }
8. Bh4
8. d6{ Keep in mind: after fortifying the pawn on  e5 , we intend to catch the bishop by ... Na5  - when our opponent allows us to, of course! 😀 }
9. c3
9. Ba7{ Moving the bishop to  b6  is recommended by Gustafsson in his  Lifetime Repertoires:  1.e4 e5  . He explains:      Before we embark on our  g5 -based adventures, we take a little timeout to avoid unpleasant  d3 - d4  surprises. There's nothing wrong with the immediate  g5  either, but this is a tad more flexible, asking White to make a move first. However, moving the bishop to  a7  is more precise since Black has a better response against  a2 - a4 . }( 9...Bb6 10.a4 { following the game of 'Prag' which went all over the world - one does not get to beat the World Champion every day. }10...Rb8 11.axb5 axb5 12.Na3⩲ { ½-½ (33),  Esipenko  (2723) -  Dubov  (2711), chess.com 2022 and 1-0 (41),  Praggnanandhaa  (2642) -  Carlsen  (2864), chess24.com 2022. } )
10. O-O( 10.a4 { is not so much to the point here, due to }10...g5 11.Bg3 b4! { . Black can now immediately put pressure on the b-file by ... Rb8 , without the bishop on  b6  blocking it. } )
10. Na5{ The Chigorin idea with ... Na5  and ... c5  is repeating itself over and over again in this course. }
11. Bc2
11. c5{ It's of vital importance to keep things under control in the center once we are planning to launch a kingside attack. White is hindered to counterstrike with  d2 - d4  then. }
12. Nbd2
12. g5{ The timing of this move is perfect! }
13. Bg3
13. Nh5
14. a3
14. Rb8{ We can perceive the modern computer-style approach of Ding, solving some of the remaining issues. Black's knight will be chased by  b2 - b4 , after which is planning the knight by  Bc2 - b3 - d5 . The rook will be placed on  c7 , protecting the  c6 -knight, so it shouldn't leave its post keeping firm control over the  d4 -square. In this way, White finds it hard to push the pawn. }
15. Kh1
15. Rb7
16. b4
16. Nc6
17. Bb3
17. Rc7{ Both sides have their chances, although White has to watch out not to be overrun on the kingside. }( 18.Bd5 g4 19.Bh4 Ne7 20.Ng1 cxb4 21.axb4 Qd7 ( 21...Rxc3 22.Ne2 Rc7 23.f4=∞ { with unclear play in  Rapport  (2764) -  Ding  (2806), 0-1 (55), Madrid 2022. } )22.f3 Rg8→ { Black has excellent attacking prospects. }23.fxg4? Nxd5 24.exd5 Qxg4∓  )
