2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6
4. Ba4
4. Nf6{ The most natural move, keeping White busy by attacking their  e4 -pawn. }
5. Nc3{ We enter the so-called Ruy Lopez Four Knights ( Tarrasch ) Variation. The reference to  Tarrasch  seems justified as he played it 19 times, with the first game played in 1907.    On the other hand,  Marco  played his first game in 1904 and had 21 games in total! Now that we are diving into chess history, the first game ever was played in 1858 by  Barnes  against  Morphy . }
5. Be7{ This line is pretty solid, adhering to our Chigorin set-up as much as possible. }
6. O-O
6. b5{ The main line, chasing the bishop and limiting our opponent's options. }
7. Bb3
7. d6{ In the Ruy Lopez style, fortifying the center. }
8. a3{ Maintaining the strong 'Fischer bishop'. }( 8.d3?! Na5! { transposes to   6.d3  . } )
8. Bg4{ Striking the iron while it's hot. }
9. h3
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3
10. Nd4{ The whole point behind this idea. Black takes White's light-squared bishop while inflicting damage to White's structure. }
11. Qg3
11. O-O{ We take the bishop on  b3  after all. }
