5. Nc3{ We enter the so-called Ruy Lopez Four Knights ( Tarrasch ) Variation. The reference to  Tarrasch  seems justified as he played it 19 times, with the first game played in 1907.    On the other hand,  Marco  played his first game in 1904 and had 21 games in total! Now that we are diving into chess history, the first game ever was played in 1858 by  Barnes  against  Morphy . }
5. Be7{ This line is pretty solid, adhering to our Chigorin set-up as much as possible. }
6. d3{ For White,  5.Nc3  has its benefits and drawbacks: the knight controls the center and could end up on  d5  but on the other hand, the ideas with  c3 - d4 , seen in the many Ruy Lopez variations, are not possible anymore. }
6. d6{ Protecting the  e5 -pawn. }( { Now }7.Be3?! { runs into }7...b5 8.Bb3 Na5⩱ { losing the bishop. Note that ... Na5  is only possible because the  e5 -pawn is defended. } )( 7.Bg5?! { has the same defect: }7...b5 8.Bb3 Na5=+ { . } )
7. a3{ We could name this new  7.a3  line after the Polish GM  Bartel  since there are just too many games from this guy in the database. Black can no longer capture the bishop with ... b5  and ... Na5  since there is a hiding place on  a2 . }
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Bg4{ Taking the chance pinning now that our opponent refrained from playing  h2 - h3 . }
9. Be3{ Anticipating ... Nc6 - d4 . }( { White is still pinned after }9.h3 Bh5⩱ { , because }10.g4? Nxg4 11.hxg4 Bxg4 { followed by ... f5  wins for Black. } )
9. Nd4{ Nonetheless, we go for this powerful move. }
10. Bxd4
10. exd4{ Taking space in the center. Not all doubled pawns are bad! 😀 }
11. Nd5( 11.Ne2? { can't be taken seriously, due to }11...Bxf3∓ { . } )
11. Nxd5
12. exd5
12. Bf6{ Black is already a bit better. It's hard to get out of the pin for White. 0-1 (49),  Lopez Idarraga  (2045) -  Granda Zuniga  (2650), Panama City 2017. }
13. Re1
13. Be5{ A wonderful move - playing for the initiative. }
14. h3
14. Bxf3
15. Qxf3
15. f5{ Next to come is ... Kh8 , ... g5  and eventually ... g4 . }
