1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6( { After }3...a6 { , the so-called 'Morphy Defense', there is immediate tension on the board - the bishop is attacked. }4.Ba4 { is played in the vast majority of games, after which the opening will branch into countless variations seen in the rest of this Lifetime Repertoire. Nonetheless, White can give up his bishop in return for quick development and a better structure. } )
4. Bxc6{ White gives up his bishop pair to give Black doubled c-pawns and get a lead in development.     This line is of special importance to me because I've spent a lot of time and effort on it, and I've genuinely enjoyed exploring the Exchange Variation from White's side (check out the  Smart Ruy Lopez, Part 1 ). }
4. dxc6( { In case of }4...bxc6?! { Black faces hard times completing development. } )( { White has many options here. One of the founding fathers of this variation,  Emanuel Lasker , played }5.d4 { as well as }5.d3 { and }5.Nc3 { here, in order to stay flexible about the placement of the king. } )
5. Nc3
5. Bc5{ A non-conventional solution to the problems posed by our opponent. We are opting for the most aggressive setup with ... Bc5  followed by ... Qd6 , while leaving the pawn on  e5  'en prise'. }( { The main line }5...f6 { is perfectly sound as well. }6.d4 exd4 7.Qxd4 Qxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd7 { , with an equal position in  Duda  (2755) -  Ragger  (2670), ½-½ (30), Prague 2020. } )
6. Nxe5
6. Bxf2+{ Let's go for it! It can't be bad to violate White's right of castling. }
7. Kxf2
7. Qd4+
8. Ke1
8. Qxe5{ Black is quite quick with his development. Next to come are ... Ne7 , ... f5 , ... Bxf5  and ... O-O-O . }
9. d4
9. Qe7{ Keeping an eye on both the pawn on  e4  and a check on  h4 . }
10. Qf3{ The most popular move for White by far. }
10. Be6{ All set for castling long. }
11. Kf2
11. Qh4+{ White has no satisfactory answer to this check: moving the king to the first rank would leave the  h1 -rook out of the game, while  g3  weakens the light squares. }
12. g3
12. Qh3{ Once again, White's position cannot be envied, as he is suffering from a 'light-square syndrome'. }
