[Black "Exchange Variation 4.Bxc6 – 5.O-O #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bb5
3. a6( { After }3...a6 { , the so-called 'Morphy Defense', there is immediate tension on the board - the bishop is attacked. }4.Ba4 { is played in the vast majority of games, after which the opening will branch into countless variations seen in the rest of this Lifetime Repertoire. Nonetheless, White can give up his bishop in return for quick development and a better structure. } )
4. Bxc6{ White gives up his bishop pair to give Black doubled c-pawns and get a lead in development.     This line is of special importance to me because I've spent a lot of time and effort on it, and I've genuinely enjoyed exploring the Exchange Variation from White's side (check out the  Smart Ruy Lopez, Part 1 ). }
4. dxc6( { In case of }4...bxc6?! { Black faces hard times completing development. } )( { White has many options here. One of the founding fathers of this variation,  Emanuel Lasker , played }5.d4 { as well as }5.d3 { and }5.Nc3 { here, in order to stay flexible about the placement of the king. } )
5. O-O{ The most ambitious move, as White stays flexible, keeping the options of  d3  or  d4  and whether the knight should be moved to  d2 ,  c3 , or  a3 , open. By the American world-class grandmaster,  Robert Byrne , the move  5.O-O  has been baptized the 'Barendregt Variation', named after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the '60s.    White has castled, whereas Black's pieces are all together back-ranked. Moreover, Black has to make an important choice on how to protect his central pawn, as White brought the threat of  Nxe5  back to life after short castling. }
5. Bg4( { Black has a broad choice of moves, for example, }5...f6 { , }5...Qd6 { , and }5...Qf6 { , and all have their merits too. However, }5...Bg4 { is definitely one of the most challenging options Black has at his disposal. }{ White normally endeavors to fetch the initiative with the aggressive  d2 - d4 , but as an immediate consequence of our move, this is no longer possible. } )
6. h3{ Asking Black where to place the bishop since White cannot allow the pin. It is beneficial for White to grab some space on the kingside, in the meantime placing his pawns on the light squares. }
6. Bh5( { This move involves a pawn sacrifice after  g2 - g4 , as Black should abandon the pin, thereby he is releasing the tension. The other uncompromising move is }6...h5 { , leading to erratic positions. } )
7. g4{ White accepts the tasty central pawn on  e5 . First, he unpins himself. }
7. Bg6{ We are planning to catch our opponent in an unknown line on the next move, which has almost never appeared in practice. }
8. Nxe5
8. Ne7{ This unknown move leads to razor-sharp play and gave me - from all the lines examined throughout  The Smart Ruy Lopez  course seen through White's spectacles - most of the shivers across my spine. }( { The main line goes }8...Qh4 9.Qf3 f6 { , }{ when White is forced to take on  g6 , which activates the  h8 -rook. }10.Nxg6 hxg6 11.Kg2 { and White will gradually solidify with accurate play. } )
9. Qf3
9. h5{ We are playing as concretely as possible, trying to get the most out of the position. }
10. g5
10. f6
11. gxf6
11. gxf6
12. Qxf6( { White will regret neglecting his king's safety after }12.Nxg6 Nxg6 { followed by ... Qd7 , ... O-O-O , and ... Rg8 . } )
12. Rg8
13. Kh2{ The only move that seems to make sense... }
13. Qd4{ White is surrounded from all angles. }
14. Nc3
14. Bg7{ Winning a piece, the ultimate reward. }
