*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B1) Italian – 4.c3 Nf6 5.d4 exd4 6.cxd4"]
[Black "Italian – 4.c3 Nf6 5.d4 exd4 6.cxd4  – 7.Nbd2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. c3{ White doesn't have to reveal their intentions yet; by starting with  4.c3 , they can still choose to play  d3  or  d4  on their next move. }
4. Nf6
5. d4{ We are entering the fray of the so-called Greco Gambit, named after mister  Greco  who played it first and gained 4 convincing victories in this system in 1620. The line became 'salonfähig' recently, with many elite players giving this dangerous line a shot. }
5. exd4
6. cxd4
6. Bb4+( { Gaining an important tempo in order to instantly strike back in the center by ... d7 - d5 , or take the pawn on  e4 . White has now three main moves: }7.Nc3 { , }7.Nbd2 { , and }7.Bd2 { . Actually, all contain venom. } )
7. Nbd2{ This move is mostly played on the top level currently. }
7. Nxe4
8. O-O
8. Nxd2
9. Bxd2
9. Bxd2{ Exchanging as many pieces as possible, relying upon our extra pawn. }
10. Qxd2
10. Ne7( { I want to prevent White's idea to break our chain by }10...O-O 11.d5!? Ne7 12.d6!? { , which would lead to unclear play. } )
11. Rfe1
11. d5{ Bringing in the  c8 -bishop and sealing off the diagonal for the bishop on  c4 . }
12. Qg5
12. dxc4{ Even though this looks dangerous, we are able to fend off the imminent dangers. }
13. Qxg7
13. Rf8
14. Ng5{ Intending  Nxh7 . }
14. Bf5{ Followed by ... Qd7  and long castling. }( { White can regain the piece with }15.Re5 Qd7 16.Rae1 O-O-O 17.Rxe7 Qxd4 { , but by then, our king has reached safety, our remaining pieces are well-placed, and we have won the  d4 -pawn. } )
