1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. c3{ White doesn't have to reveal their intentions yet; by starting with  4.c3 , they can still choose to play  d3  or  d4  on their next move. }
4. Nf6
5. d4{ We are entering the fray of the so-called Greco Gambit. The line became 'socially acceptable' recently, with many elite players trying their luck with White in this dangerous line. }
5. exd4
6. e5
6. d5
7. Bb5
7. Ne4
8. cxd4
8. Bb6{ Black should maintain pressure on the central point  d4 . He will follow up with short castling, ... Bg4  and ... f6 . }( 8...Bb4+?! { is often played by youngsters. Unfortunately, it can't be recommended since White gets the free hand after which he will have the upper hand in the center after }9.Nbd2 Nxd2 10.Bxd2 Bxd2+ 11.Qxd2± { . The c-pawn is backward, while White has the superior pawn structure due to its outpost on  e5 . } )
9. Nc3{ An important recipe for our Greco-meal. Black's energetic knight will be undermined. }
9. O-O
10. Be3{ Another strong move according to the antique theme from Aron Nimzowitsch: 'Überdeckung' (overprotection). Now that the  d4 -pawn is protected by the knight and bishop, the queen can move to  c2  (or sometimes  b3  or  a4 ). }
10. Bg4{ Pinning the knight, enhancing the pressure on  d4 . }
11. h3( 11.Bxc6 { is premature. }11...bxc6 { Black gets extra options here, such as ... c6 - c5 , whereas White is not ready yet for the opening of the position. }12.h3 Bh5 { Of course, Black keeps the pressure alive. }13.O-O ( 13.Qc2 c5!  )13...f6→ { With serious pressure on  f3 , after which White is more or less forced to play the weakening  g2 - g4 . } )
11. Bh5
12. Qc2
12. Nxc3
13. bxc3
13. f6{ Breaking White's strong pawn chain. }
14. Bxc6
14. Bxf3( 14...bxc6 { is one of the rare occasions where we shouldn't follow the choice of the World Champion: }15.exf6 Bxf3 { The issue presents itself. }16.fxg7 { White doesn't stop gobbling up pawns. }16...Rf7 17.gxf3⩲ { This is a dangerous position for Black, even when Magnus Carlsen has the controls, ½-½ (44),  Giri  (2764) -  Carlsen   (2862), chess24.com 2020. } )
15. gxf3
15. bxc6{ Black exerts pressure on the central  e5  and the f-file. One more objective: pin down our rook at  f3 . }
16. f4
16. Qe7{ Connecting the rooks, preparing for ... c5 . }
17. a4( 17.Ke2 c5!⇆  )
17. Ba5( { There was nothing wrong with }17...a5!? { either. }18.Rg1 c5⇆ { , 0-1  (41),  Remizov  (2411) -  Shuvalova  (2476), Cheliabinsk 2021. } )
18. Ke2
18. c5( { Followed by }19.Rhg1 Rf7 { . Black is waging guerilla warfare on several points in the extended white wall of pawns. ½-½ (39),  Harika  (2511) -  Goryachkina  (2602), Sitges 2021. } )
