[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. c3{ White doesn't have to reveal their intentions yet; by starting with  4.c3 , they can still choose to play  d3  or  d4  on their next move. }
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. h6{ We ruled all of White's popular  Bg5  out in one go. The theory is developing and White is trying to find ways to profit from Black's early ... h6 . Nonetheless, this is not so easy since this little pawn move is useful in almost all Italian positions. Moreover, it serves us excellent as - compared to the other main lines with  5...a6  or  5...a5  - there is little to know. }
6. O-O( 6.h3 d6 7.O-O O-O 8.Re1 { transposes. } )
6. d6
7. h3
7. Bb6{ A fine touch of prophylaxis. What I like about this move is that we tuck the bishop away in only one move, sparing one move if you compare it to the ... a6  & ... Ba7  lines. }
8. Re1
8. O-O
9. d4( 9.Nbd2 { transposes. } )
9. Re8{ White's pawn push is premature. }
10. d5{ What else? }
10. Ne7{ Black's bishop shines wonderfully over the  a7 - g1  diagonal, while we turn up the heat by ... Ne7 - g6  and eventually ... Nf4 . }
