3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. c3{ White doesn't have to reveal their intentions yet; by starting with  4.c3 , they can still choose to play  d3  or  d4  on their next move. }
4. Nf6
5. d3
5. h6{ We ruled all of White's popular  Bg5  out in one go. The theory is developing and White is trying to find ways to profit from Black's early ... h6 . Nonetheless, this is not so easy since this little pawn move is useful in almost all Italian positions. Moreover, it serves us excellent as - compared to the other main lines with  5...a6  or  5...a5  - there is little to know. }
6. b4{ Gaining space on the queenside is quite a different approach than White's recurring  Nb1 - d2 - c4 - e3  or  f1 - g3 / e3  or  d3 - d4  positional project. }( 6.h3 d6 7.O-O O-O 8.Re1 { transposes. } )
6. Bb6
7. a4{ We won't let our bishop be trapped! }
7. a6{ Creating 'luft' for the bishop meanwhile halting the b-pawn's advance. }( { The ignorant }7...a5? { would lose a pawn by force, after }8.b5 Ne7 9.Nxe5⩲ { . } )
8. O-O( 8.Nbd2 d6 { transposes. } )
8. O-O
9. Nbd2( 9.Re1 d6 { would transpose. } )( { After }9.a5 { the pawns are fixed. This line transposes to }{  8.a5 . } )
9. d6
10. Re1{ This trendy line was recently played by elite players like  Carlsen ,  Giri  and  Dominguez . White chooses the shortcut: postponing or abandoning the plan with  h2 - h3 , aiming for the central pawn push  d3 - d4  and possibly moving the bishop to  f1  and the knight to  c4 . }( 10.a5 { transposes. } )
{ The preparatory }10. Be6{ allows doubled pawn on the e-file. On the other hand, we get an open f-file for the benefit of our heavy pieces, while the  e6 -pawn is protecting a lot of strong squares surrounding. }( { I would refrain from }10...Ne7 { due to }11.d4 exd4 ( 11...Ng6 12.Bf1  )12.cxd4 d5 13.e5!± { , 1-0 (44),  Carlsen  (2847) -  So  (2770), chess24.com 2021. } )
11. Qb3
11. Re8{ A useful move endorsing the  e6 -point, meanwhile getting ready for the ... d6 - d5  break. }
12. Bxe6
12. Rxe6{ Black is aiming now for the liberating ... d6 - d5 . }
13. Nc4{ 1-0 (41),  Zavarce Sayago  (2210) -  Cancino , San Antonio del Tachira 2013. }
13. d5{ With this move we immediately equalize. }
14. Nxb6
14. cxb6
15. Be3
15. dxe4{ The fastest road to an equal position. }
16. dxe4
16. Nxe4{ There will revolve a fight around the central pawn on  e5 . }
17. Bxb6
17. Qxb6
18. Rxe4
18. Rae8{ The pawn is well safeguarded, while White should pay attention to any pawn rush forward by  f5  and  e4 . }
