[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. b4{ This opening is based on quick tactics after this pawn sacrifice. The Evans Gambit still has a dangerous reputation to this day and makes many Black players tremble! However, there's no reason to be afraid. In fact, we should be happy to see it on the board. That said, Black needs to know a number of accurate moves to defend against the sharp attacks that White can launch. }
4. Bxb4
5. c3{ White supports  d2 - d4  and has  Qb3  at his disposal now. }
5. Ba5( 5...Bc5?! { is a bit dubious because White can seize the center with tempo ( d2 - d4 ). The first game in this gambit dates back to the year 1829 by, of course, Mr. Evans! }6.O-O !? Nf6 7.d4 exd4 8.cxd4 Bb6 9.e5 d5 10.exf6 dxc4 11.Re1+ Kf8 12.Ba3+ Kg8 13.d5 Na5 14.Be7 Qd7 15.fxg7 Kxg7 16.Qd2 Qg4 17.Qc3+ { . Through a beautiful finishing combination, Evans puts an end to all of Black's illusions. }17...Kg8 18.Qxh8+ Kxh8 19.Bf6+ Qg7 20.Re8# { . 1-0 (20),  Evans  -  McDonnell , London 1829. } )
6. O-O
6. Nf6{ The least committing continuation for us, as we are not running into trouble by any king-in-the-middle types of positions. }
7. d4
7. O-O{ The king found shelter, as it turns out White wasn't threatening to win a pawn. }
8. dxe5
8. Nxe4
9. Bd5
9. Nc5{ The knight finds a spot somewhere near the center. }
10. Ng5( 10.Ba3 { can be met by }10...Bb6!⩱ { . } )
10. h6{ Without any detours, the next line is leading to simplifications. }( 10...Ne6? { runs into trouble, such as mate! }11.Qh5 { , played by Mr. Chigorin himself! }11...Nxg5 12.Bxg5 Qe8 13.Bf6! { , 1-0 (30),  Chigorin  -  Shabelsky , correspondence 1884. } )( 10...Qe7!? { , }{ guarding the  c5 -knight and  f7 , while keeping the knight on  c5  for a while, is also good enough. }11.Qh5 { ( }11.Re1 h6! { )   }11...h6 { and compared to the positions with the knight }{ on  e6 , the exchange }12.Ne4 Nxe4 { is favorable for us. } )
11. Nxf7( 11.Qh5 Qe7! { but not }11...hxg5 { , due to Chigorin's }12.Bxg5+- { followed by  Bf6 . } )
11. Rxf7
12. Bxf7+
12. Kxf7
13. Qd5+
13. Ne6{ White will try to use his f-pawn as a battering ram. Nonetheless, we have some inventive defensive resources. }
14. f4
14. Bb6+
15. Kh1
15. Ne7{ Trying to block the advance of the pawn. }
16. Qf3( { In case of }16.Qd3 Nc5! 17.Qc2 d6! { , }{ we successfully set up a blockade on the  f5 -square. }18.exd6 Nf5!  )
16. Nf5( { Precise play is urged for. }16...g6? 17.f5! gxf5 18.Qh5++- { , 1-0 (25),  Heinrichsen  -  Walbrodt , Berlin 1897. } )
17. g4
17. Nh4{ The blockade is lifted, but instead, we get excellent attacking chances against White's unprotected king. }
18. Qg3
18. d6{ Launching the bishop on  c8 . }
19. f5
19. Kg8{ Paving the way for the  c8 -bishop to the long diagonal. }
