6. d6{ The most solid continuation, fortifying the center. }( 6...exd4 { leads to complications, although it is a very solid move as well. }7.O-O! { It doesn't matter that another pawn is lost. White wants to develop the pieces as quickly as possible! }7...Bxc3? 8.Nxc3 dxc3 9.Ba3!→ { . The bishop prevents Black from castling. 1-0 (25),  P. Morphy  -  E. Morphy , New Orleans 1850. } )
7. O-O( { Please keep in mind that after }7.Ng5 { we can simply protect }{ our  f7 -pawn with }7...Nh6! { . } )( { Also, White doesn't win a piece with }7.d5 Nce7 8.Qa4+ { , as Black can save his bishop with }8...c6∓ { . } )
7. Bg4{ This is not the main continuation, but the move ... Bg4  is approved by the strongest engines. }
8. Bb5{ White is abandoning the plan consisting of a kingside attack. Instead, he is aiming for a walk-over in the center. }
8. exd4{ As the temperature was rising revolving  e5 , this is the time to trade. }
9. cxd4
9. Nge7{ Completing development, relying on the next response against  d4 - d5 . }
10. d5
10. a6{ As it appears, White cannot win a piece. The good thing for us is that we have some pocket money in the shape of an extra pawn. }
11. Ba4
11. b5
12. dxc6
12. bxa4{ Losing our 'pocket money' - i.e. the extra pawn - but in return, we have the more active pieces. }
13. Qxa4
13. Bxf3{ Putting the white king in harm's way. }
14. Qxa5
14. Bxe4
15. Re1
15. Bxc6
16. Qg5
16. Kf8{ Following up with ... Ng6  while being a pawn up. Black has a big advantage. }
