6. d4
6. d6{ The most solid continuation, fortifying the center. }( 6...exd4 { leads to complications, although it is a very solid move as well. }7.O-O! { It doesn't matter that another pawn is lost. White wants to develop the pieces as quickly as possible! }7...Bxc3? 8.Nxc3 dxc3 9.Ba3!→ { . The bishop prevents Black from castling. 1-0 (25),  P. Morphy  -  E. Morphy , New Orleans 1850. } )
7. Qb3( { Please keep in mind that after }7.Ng5 { we can simply protect }{ our  f7 -pawn with }7...Nh6! { . } )( { Also, White doesn't win a piece with }7.d5 Nce7 8.Qa4+ { , as Black can save his bishop with }8...c6∓ { . } )
7. Qd7{ This move comes in use regularly in this Lifetime Repertoire − please have a look for a similar idea in the  Göring Gambit . }( { The  f7 -square needs protection while ... e7  is a bad square for the queen as shown by }7...Qe7? 8.d5! { White is threatening to pick up a piece }{ with  Qa4 +, forcing }8...Nd4 { with unnecessary complications. } )
8. dxe5
8. Bb6{ Threatening to exchange White's strongest minor piece with ... Na5 . }
9. Bb5
9. a6
10. Ba4( { Frankly, I don't understand why }10.Bxc6 { was played 18 times in my database, because Black solves all of his problems with }10...Qxc6 11.O-O Be6 { , and enjoys a large advantage because of his bishop pair and better structure. } )
10. Nge7
11. O-O
11. dxe5{ This doesn't win the pawn back, but it does simplify the position to our advantage. }
12. Nxe5
12. Qe6{ Proposing a trade of queens, while preparing for castling. Black was slightly better in ½-½  Benedetto  (2125) -  Van Habberney  (2185), ICCF email 2016, because of his lead in development and superior pawn structure. }
