2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. O-O
4. Nf6
5. d4{ In 2009, 13 years after I first encountered it, this system caught my attention once again when one of my students faced it. I was deeply impressed by it during my time playing in the B-group of Wijk aan Zee, where I had the opportunity to watch all the games of the A-group. Specifically, I vividly recall how the white player Sergei Movsesian expertly outplayed Michael Adams in a truly captivating manner. }
5. Bxd4( 5...exd4 6.e5! { is the famous Max Lange Attack. It's a sharp and aggressive option for White. After }6...d5 7.exf6 dxc4 { , they can choose between }8.fxg7 { and }8.Re1+ { . Theoretically, Black is doing fine against both, but I find our defensive task after  5...Bxd4  much easier. } )
6. Nxd4
6. Nxd4
7. f4
7. d6
8. fxe5
8. dxe5
9. Bg5{ We transposed to the lines arising after  7.Bg5 , with the only difference that White can opt for some alternate moves. }
9. Qe7
10. c3
10. Ne6{ Black deviates from the main line arising after  7.Bg5  and  8.f4 . }( { Movsesian stated in his comments on this old game that }10...Be6 11.Na3 { can be considered the 'main line' of this rare variation. Here, as can be seen in the main line, we take on  c4 . } )
11. Bxe6
11. Bxe6{ Black is being helped to tuck the king away at the queenside. White is too underdeveloped to pose any kind of trouble. }
12. Bxf6
12. gxf6
13. Na3
13. Rg8{ Aiming for the king! }
14. Kh1
14. Qd7{ After which the problem of long castling is solved. Black has the stronger minor piece and can attack the  e4 -pawn by ... Rg4 . 0-1 (64)  Alarcon Casellas  (2378) -  Bachmann  (2652), Barcelona 2014. }
