[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. O-O
4. Nf6
5. c3{ And so we enter the Albin Gambit, not to be confused with the Albin Countergambit  1.d4  d5  2.c4 e5 . It is not as well-known as some other gambits, but it can catch unprepared opponents off guard.    However, Black has several ways to decline the gambit and try to hold onto the extra pawn. One common approach is to play  5...d6 , which allows Black to develop their pieces.    Overall, the Albin Gambit is a sharp and dynamic line that can lead to exciting games for both sides. It requires accurate play from White to justify the pawn sacrifice, while Black must be prepared to weather the early storm and counterattack in the center. }
5. Nxe4{ Accepting the challenge, we only need one move to get the king to the 'green pastures'. }
6. Bd5( 6.Qe2? { is simply bad because of }6...d5! { . } )
6. Nf6{ White is very welcome to trade their light-squared bishop. }
7. Bxc6
7. dxc6
8. Nxe5
8. O-O{ We enjoy a small but lasting advantage thanks to the bishop pair. }
