9. Ne7{ Blocking the check and the e-file. Black is doing fine here as castling is guaranteed on the next move. On the other hand, we still need to deal with  Bg5 . }
10. Nc3
10. O-O
11. Bg5
11. c6{ Allowing the weakening of the kingside, since our knight comes to the rescue to fill the gap! }
12. Bxf6
12. gxf6
13. Be4
13. d5{ The freeing move - before moving the knight to our king! }
14. Bc2
14. Ng6{ There is nothing left to long for White. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "B8) Italian – Albin Gambit 4.O-O Nf6 5.c3"]
[Black "Italian – Albin Gambit 4.O-O Nf6 5.c3 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Bc4{ We enter the Italian Game. White aims their bishop at our weakest point: the  f7 -pawn. }
3. Bc5( { This variation is named the 'Giuoco Piano', which means 'quiet game'. We avoid the complications arising after }3...Nf6 4.Ng5!? { . } )
4. O-O
4. Nf6
5. c3{ And so we enter the Albin Gambit, not to be confused with the Albin Countergambit  1.d4  d5  2.c4 e5 . It is not as well-known as some other gambits, but it can catch unprepared opponents off guard.    However, Black has several ways to decline the gambit and try to hold onto the extra pawn. One common approach is to play  5...d6 , which allows Black to develop their pieces.    Overall, the Albin Gambit is a sharp and dynamic line that can lead to exciting games for both sides. It requires accurate play from White to justify the pawn sacrifice, while Black must be prepared to weather the early storm and counterattack in the center. }
5. Nxe4{ Accepting the challenge, we only need one move to get the king to the 'green pastures'. }
6. d4( 6.Qe2? { is simply bad because of }6...d5! { . } )
6. exd4{ As we will soon see, this is easier said than done. The e-file has been opened, which makes that the knight will be easy prey for White's major pieces. }
7. cxd4
7. d5{ We are following a very concrete line and the main line of the Albin Gambit. }
8. dxc5( 8.Bb5? Bd6 { leaves Black a pawn up. } )( 8.Re1 Bb4 {  transposes  to }{   }7.Re1 d5 8.cxd4 Bb4 { . } )
8. dxc4{ The knight on  e4  is balancing on a chord. Surprisingly, we can maintain the knight and, even better, our advantage! }
9. Qxd8+
9. Kxd8{ At first sight, this may seem dangerous to many players who are not playing the Berlin Wall with Black. }
10. Rd1+
10. Bd7
11. Be3
11. Kc8{ Seen this before by the Berlin Wall adherents. }( { The text move is even stronger than }11...Ke7 12.Na3 Be6 13.Nd4 Nxd4 14.Bxd4∞ { . } )
12. Na3
12. c3{ We can afford to stick to the pawn as White's pieces are not that active yet. }
13. bxc3
13. Nxc3
14. Rd3
14. Ne4( { Black is more than OK. For instance, }15.Ng5 Nxg5 16.Bxg5 a5 17.Rad1 Be6 18.R1d2 a4 { This is the way we solve the issue of the cornered rook, by bringing it back in the game via  a5 . } )
