16. Qf2{ The white pieces have taken offensive positions. We should be careful with our next moves! }( 16.Qxb4?! Bxb4 17.Rab1 { , 0-1 (66),  Roberson  (2438) -  Maurizzi  (2506), Bastia 2022. The French talent could improve on his play with }17...a5! 18.f5 O-O { ⩱ }{ . } )
16. Qc3{ A very strong defensive resource. If White pushes his pawns forward by  f5  and  e6 , Black can just take the pawn twice due to the hanging bishop at  e3 . }
17. f5
17. O-O-O{ Of course! As a rule of thumb, we castle to the side were White doesn't proceed with his operations. }( { In case of }18.Rab1 { Black can play }18...Bb6!Ν { . My first choice. In case of  Qe2 , Black can repel  Qa6 + with ... Kb7 . }19.a4 c5!  )( { Or   }18...Rhe8 19.Qe2 Qa3 { , which is better for Black, but catchy. 0-1 (65),  Sebastjaniuk  -  Speisser , ICCF email 2014. } )( { The position is not merely risky for Black, as the following line shows:   }18...Bb6 19.Rb3? Qc4! 20.Rfb1 c5 21.Ne2 Rhe8-+ { White has run out of active plans, with Black picking up the pieces. } )( { Or   }18.e6 fxe6 { One of the main points concerning our piece set-up (with  Qc3  and  Bc5 ). }19.fxe6 Bxe6! { Making use of the pin. } )
