13. Qb6{ Tensions are rising across the diagonal! We are also thinking about long castling now. }( { Black should avoid }13...O-O 14.Qd3 f6 15.Nd2 Nxd2 16.Qxd2 Qe8 17.Nf3 Bxe3+ 18.Qxe3 { after which his pawns are fixed, 1-0 (78),  Adhiban  (2660) -  Ganguly  (2625), Tornelo INT 2021. } )
14. Qd3
14. Bc8{ With the aim of playing ... Ba6 , provoking  c2 - c4 , after which we try to undermine the knight's  d4 -foothold by opening the d-file and putting a rook on  d8 . }( 14...a5!? { is another playable line, although it is a bit slow to my taste. }15.Nd2 { 0-1 (75),  Padmini  (2370) -  Khademalsharieh  (2494), Krasnaya Polyana 2021. }15...Bxd4!Ν 16.Bxd4 c5 { The idea is to clear the way for the light-squared bishop (... Bc6 ). } )( 14...Bg4? 15.Nc3! Nxc3 16.Qxc3 { is just bad for Black since White gained control over the  c5 -square. } )
15. c4
15. Bg4{ Taking control of  d1 , making the position of the knight at  d4  more wobbly. Black aims to open up the d-file holding the knight at gunpoint. On top of that, White can no longer endorse the knight by  Rd1  while he should take into account the tactic ... Bg4 - e2 ! }
16. Nc3( 16.Nd2 O-O-O!⩱  )
16. Nxc3{ We are on unexplored territory now. }
17. Qxc3
17. dxc4{ We shouldn't allow  cxd5 ,  cxd5  (followed by  Rc1 , for example). }( 17...O-O-O { , }{ intending to take back with the rook while increasing the pressure on  d4 , was possible as well. } )
18. bxc4( 18.Qxc4? O-O-O { The knight loses its ground at  d4 . } )( 18.h3 { is probably White's best, after which we can liquidate into the endgame by }18...O-O-O { and taking on  d4 . } )
18. O-O-O{ The whole strategy behind ... Bg4  is presenting itself. White cannot hold the  d4 -square since  Rd1  can't be played with the bishop at  g4 . }
