3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6{ The present theoretical status of  4...Nf6  remains impervious to the once-intimidating Scotch main line — endorsed by none other than the legendary Sir Garry Kasparov. }( 4...Bc5 { appears to be another viable option, albeit with less defined parameters compared to }4...Nf6 { . } )
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6{ The characteristic outlines of the Scotch, resulting into irregular and very interesting positions. Let the battle begin! }
6. e5{ Grabbing space and stopping Black's central pawn thrust ... d7 - d5 . }
6. Qe7{ The queen on  e2  is hurting White more than Black's ... Qe7 . }( { White has it all after }6...Nd5?! 7.c4 Nb6 8.Bd3 { - the better structure AND development! } )
7. Qe2
7. Nd5{ Taking stock, we are better developed and we will be able to hit White's forward pawn in due time by ... f6  or ... d6 .    Nonetheless, the problems we are facing aren't negligible: our knight will be chased away by  c4 , and our pawn structure is weakened ( c6 ,  c7 ). }
8. c4
8. Ba6{ Pinning the pawn and maintaining the  d5 -outpost for the knight. Another comforting thought of prolonging the knight's stay on  d5 , is that White doesn't have the extra option of  Nc3 . }( { Another main line, but beyond the scope of our LTR, is }8...Nb6 9.Nc3 Qe6 10.Qe4 Ba6 11.b3 O-O-O { , 1-0 (77),  Kasparov  (2851) -  Adams  (2715), internet 2000. } )
9. Nd2
9. g6{ We are glad to adhere to this course of action: fianchettoing the bishop undermines the pivotal  e5 -pawn. We have the support of the best positional player the world has ever known (together with Carlsen?! 😀). }
10. b3
10. Bg7{ In for a penny, in for a pound. }
11. Bb2
11. Nb4{ The fork is highly unpleasant for White. The move being called for is long castling, unfortunately for White, that loses the  a2 -pawn. }
12. Nf3
12. c5{ Opening up the  a8 - h1  diagonal. }
13. g3
13. d5( { This is even more concrete than }13...O-O { , although a transposition is likely. } )
14. Bg2
14. dxc4
15. bxc4
15. O-O
16. O-O
16. Rad8{ The position is balanced, but I'd definitely prefer the black pieces: at the cost of having doubled pawns, the black pieces are more actively positioned. There can follow ... Qe6 , ... Nc6 - d4  and eventually ... Rb8 . }( { For example, }17.Rfd1 Qe6 18.Bf1 h6 19.Ne1 Nc6 20.f4 Rxd1 21.Rxd1 Rb8⇆ { ½-½ (44),  Franks  (2348) -  Rallabandi  (2485), ICCF email 2019. } )
