10. d6{ We must be very accurate here with the move order, meanwhile we should act firmly breaking the central white pawn chain. }( { For instance, }10...Bg7? 11.Qf2! Nf6 12.Be2! { Compared to the main line, we could take here on  e5 . Now are knight starts drifting. }12...Ne4 13.Qe3 f5 14.Nd2!± { Black is much worse due to his inferior pawn structure. He doesn't have the necessary pressure against the  e5 -pawn, 0-1 (26),  Sandor  (2420) -  Petran  (2470), Budapest 1995. } )( 10...f6!? { was played in the renowned Kasparov-Karpov game. }11.Ba3 Qf7? 12.Qd2 Nb6 13.c5 Bxf1 14.cxb6 axb6?! 15.e6!! { An elegant stroke, after which Kasparov - in his own words - ' began to shake with excitement '. }( 15.Bxf8 Bxg2 16.Qxg2 Rxf8 { Black has enough pawns for the piece. } )15...dxe6 ( { The point is that after }15...Qxe6+ 16.Kxf1 Bxa3 17.Nxa3 Rxa3 { Karpov would lose his queen by }18.Re1 { . } )16.Bxf8 Rd8 17.Qb2 Bxg2 18.Qxg2!± { The point of  e6  comes to the surface:  c6  is hanging! 1-0 (44),  Kasparov  (2770) -  Karpov  (2730), Tilburg 1991. } )
11. Qd2{ The knight is hanging on  d5 . }
11. Nb6
12. Ba3
12. c5{ Locking the  a3 -bishop down. }
13. Nc3
13. dxe5
14. Nd5
14. Nxd5{ Given the fact that White cannot win the  a6 -bishop with  Qxd5  and  Qc6 +, this is quite a risky operation. }
15. Qxd5
15. Rd8( { Please refrain from }15...exf4+?? 16.Be2 Rd8 17.Qc6+ Qd7 { as it is no longer mate on  d2 . } )
16. Qxe5( 16.Qc6+ Qd7! { with the counterthreat on  d2 . } )
16. Qxe5+
17. fxe5
17. Bb7{ Both pawns are weak, although I would slightly prefer Black because of the more active pieces  (which is not surprising as author of this LTR 😀). }
