1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. Nxd4
4. Nf6{ The current state of theory is that the 4... Nf6  line is bulletproof against the once-so-scary main line of the Scotch, used by the greatest on earth ( Garry Kasparov ).     4...Bc5  seems to be another decent response, although it is not as 'demarcated' as  4...Nf6 . }
5. Nxc6
5. bxc6
6. e5
6. Qe7
7. Qe2
7. Nd5{ Taking stock, we are better developed and we will be able to hit white's forward pawn in due time by ... f7 - f6  or ... d7 - d6 . Nonetheless, the problems we are facing aren't negligible: i.e., our knight will be chased by  c4  and our pawn structure is weakened ( c6 ,  c7 ). }
8. h4{ White's development is impeded so they play  8.h4  to facilitate  Bg5  or possibly  Rh3 . In case Black castles kingside, the advanced h-pawn will give White attacking chances, especially if Black plays ... g6 , which is a common move in the Scotch.    The move is relatively uncommon, and it has been played by various grandmasters over the years, including Alexander Morozevich, Rustam Kasimdzhanov, and Hikaru Nakamura, among others. These players have used  8.h4  as a surprise weapon or a way to avoid well-known theoretical lines and steer the game into uncharted territory. }
8. Qe6{ This variation was brought into fashion again by  Vladimir Kramnik . The queen makes way for the bishop at  e7 , while in case of  c4   Nb6 , Black hits the  c4 -pawn 3 times, causing problems for White to protect it. }
9. Nd2
9. a5{ This is not the most topical continuation, nonetheless, it is the most promising. }( { The continuation }9...d6 { is also very playable. After }10.exd6 Bxd6 11.Nc4 Bc5 12.a3 O-O 13.Qxe6 Bxe6 { White merely has a minor theoretical edge, as recently seen in  Yu  (2713) -  Mamedyarov   (2767), ½-½ (36), Belgrade 2022. } )
10. c4
10. Nb6( { The move }10...Nb4 { looks threatening and creates a precarious situation, but after }11.Nf3! { it is White who lays the snare. }11...Qg6 ( { Don't be lured into the following trap: }11...Qf5 12.Nd4 Qg6 13.h5! { Trapping the queen. } )12.h5! Qc2 13.a3 Qxe2+ 14.Kxe2!⩲ { The black knight should retreat. } )
11. Nf3
11. Bb4+{ The right plan, heading for short castling after which White is way behind in development. }
12. Bd2
12. Bxd2+( 12...d5 { was less convincing. }13.exd6 Bxd2+ 14.Kxd2 cxd6 15.Nd4 Qxe2+ 16.Bxe2 { . After this series of moves, White was only helped by the exchanges in  Studer  (2546) -  Khotenashvili  (2446), 1-0  (40), Caleta 2020. } )
13. Nxd2
13. O-O{ White's problems come to the light: he is way underdeveloped and can no longer castle kingside. }
14. O-O-O
14. a4{ The best move here for Black, although  Robson 's  14...Re8  also led to a promising position. The rook can meddle with the affairs via  a5  and eventually  c5 . White's king is highly vulnerable. }
15. h5( 15.f4 a3! { This line effectively stresses the vulnerability of the white king on  c1 . }16.b3 d5 17.exd6 Qxd6 { clearly shows White's vulnerability on the dark squares. } )
15. h6{ There is no need to allow  h5 - h6 , we are not in a rush. }
16. Re1
16. d5{ The configuration with pawns on  a4  and  d5  is powerful and leaves White no choice but to trade down to an endgame. Otherwise, he would be 'overflown' by ... Ba6 , ... Rb8  and so on. }
17. exd6
17. cxd6
18. Qxe6
18. Bxe6
19. Rh4
19. Ra5{ Bringing the rook into play, with good prospects. }
