5. Nxc6
5. bxc6{ White has options now, as he hasn't committed to  Nc3  yet. }
6. Qe2{ A highly peculiar choice, this queen move so early in the game, meanwhile blocking the  f1 -bishop. }( { In the main line of the Scotch, }6.e5 Qe7 { , }7.Qe2 { is more logical, unpinning and forcing the knight to leave  f6 . } )
6. Bc5
7. e5( { Nepo once chose the even more peculiar }7.g3? { , leaving all his pieces in their starting positions. }7...O-O 8.Bg2 d5 { is simply bad for White. }{ ½-½ (35),  Nepomniachtchi  (2705) -  Kramnik  (2777), Berlin 2015. } )
7. Nd5
8. c4{ This can be considered the main move here. }
8. Nb6( { A very common continuation is }8...Ne7 9.Be3 Bxe3 10.Qxe3 { , after which White has a slight pull. ½-½ (38),  Yu  (2734) -  Wei Yi  (2737), Taizhou 2015. } )
9. Qg4
9. g6( { For the Tigran Petrosian fans, whose trademark was the exchange sacrifice, I give the following line: }9...O-O!? 10.Bh6 g6 11.Bxf8 Qxf8 12.Be2 { , 1-0 (24),  Noritsyn  (2512) -  Terletsky  (2307), chess.com 2020. } )
10. Bg5
10. d5{ Two queens are hanging. }
11. Qg3
11. Be7{ Guarding the dark squares. }
12. h4
12. h6{ Chasing the aggressor. }
13. Be3
13. Nxc4{ This isn't to win a pawn, but to trade White's light-squared bishop. }
14. Bxc4
14. dxc4
15. Nc3
15. Bf5{ Followed by installing the bishop on  d3 , Black is doing well. 0-1 (45),  Feuerstack  (2450) -  Kollars  (2583), Lueneburg 2019. }
