5. bxc6{ White has options now, as he hasn't committed to  Nc3  yet. }
6. Bd3( { This is one of them! According to Gustafsson, in his  1.e4 e5  Lifetime Repertoires, this is a logical and very solid move, and I agree, as it is a decent developing move whereas it doesn't allow any pins after }6.Nc3 Bb4 { . } )
6. d5{ Of course! We undertake action in the center. Please notice the difference to the main lines when  Nc3  and ... Bb4  are included. }
7. e5{ In Step 6 of the renowned  Step Method  series, we learned that this can turn out badly for White. }
7. Ng4{ With ... Bc5  & ... Qh4  to follow. }
8. Bf4
8. Bc5{ Hitting  f2 . }
9. Bg3
9. O-O{ With the idea of ... f7 - f6  and taking on  e5 . }
10. O-O( 10.h3 Nxe5! 11.Bxe5 Re8 12.f4 Qh4+ { is causing White to shiver from top to toe. } )
10. f5{ Leaving White with the highly unpleasant choice of opening up the f-file with  exf6  or allowing the loss of a piece by  f5 - f4 ... well, definitely not the last choice! }
11. exf6
11. Qxf6{ Do I need to say more? Black is much better. }
