9. O-O( { I am less convinced by }9...d4 { . }10.Bg5 { The most popular choice on highest level. }O-O 11.Nd2 a5!? { This was tried by Giri, in order to block the pawn majority, and is a good alternative. }( 11...Bg4 12.Nf3 h6 13.Bxf6 Bxf6 14.h3 Be6 15.b4⩲ { Black's pawn is blocked, while White enjoys the majority on the queenside. 1-0 (39),  Shankland  (2708) -  Vidit  (2727), Kolkata 2021. } )12.Nb3 ( { Another way to go is }12.Re1 h6 13.Bh4 c5 { White puts some pressure across the e-file, though Black has some defensive resources. }14.Qf3 Ra6! { The rook lift makes that Black's control across the 6th rank is increased. }15.h3 Qc7∞ { Followed by ... Bb7 . } )12...h6 13.Bh4 g5!? { The position is getting very wild, which isn't my cup of tea. }14.Bg3 c5 { ½-½ (33),  Najer  (2635) -  Giri  (2780), Khanty-Mansiysk 2019. }{ Wild complications would have arisen after }15.f4!? { when ... Ng4  or ... Ra6  leads to highly unclear play. } )
10. cxd5
10. Nxd5{ Black's pawn structure is slightly damaged, but on the other hand we can maintain the strong position of our knight creating a foothold with ... c6 . }
11. Be4
11. c6{ As White opens fire on the  d5 -point, our response is straight and clear: bolstering the defences here. }
12. Bd2
12. Rb8{ Powerful play by the former World Champion Anand, not giving his opponent a break. }
13. Qc2
13. Bf6{ He is using his lead in development optimally, not wasting time on the slow ... h7 - h6 . }
14. Bc3
14. Nxc3{ In the resulting positions, Black is very flexible which makes it hard to guess for White where the queen (and other pieces) will be placed. }
15. Nxc3
15. g6{ Restricting the  e4 -bishop. Black relies fully on his lead in development and his 2 powerful bishops. }
16. Rac1
16. Qa5{ Exerting full pressure on  a2 ,  b2  and  c3 . }
17. Na4
17. c5
18. b3
18. c4( { A beautiful concept, illuminating the strength of the bishop pair over the unstable knight. }19.Rfd1 ( 19.bxc4 Rb4 { As we know, knights need a foothold in the center. Here, the knight is pretty far from that, drifting. }20.Nc3 Rxc4 { The piece is lost. } )19...Be6 20.Rb1 Rfc8 21.b4 Rxb4 22.Rxb4 Qxb4 23.g3 c3 24.Bd5 Bxd5 25.Rxd5 Rc4 { , 0-1 (25),  Gavrilescu  (2518) -  Anand  (2751), Warsaw 2022. } )
