[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. d4
3. exd4
4. c3
4. dxc3
5. Nxc3
5. Bc5{ This move was first used in practice by Paul Morphy in 1857. Strangely enough, it didn't get many followers for over 165 years, but the engines like Black's bishop move. }( { That being said, }5...d6 { is completely fine too and transposes to   5.Bc4  d6  6.Nxc3   after }6.Bc4 { . } )
6. Bc4
6. d6{ Please reckon with  Bxf7 + and  Qd5 . Here the  c5 -bishop is guarded. }
7. Qb3( { Mr. Paul Morphy himself was the first ever to encounter the Göring Gambit! }7.h3?! { Stopping ... Bg4 , but way too slow. }7...Be6! { Defusing the threat across the diagonal. }8.Bb5 Nge7! { Black is much better and Morphy went on to win, 0-1 (31),  Meek  -  Morphy , New York 1857. } )( { Occupying the  g5 -square is not great for White: }7.Bg5 Nge7! { after which we shouldn't worry about  Ng5  any longer. } )
7. Qd7{ The similar idea as in our main line. Black is preparing for ... Na5 , while guarding  f7 . }
8. Nd5
8. Nge7{ Now that the  d5 -knight blocks the diagonal, we take the chance to prepare castling. }
9. Qc3
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Nxd5
11. exd5
11. Ne5{ The last important move, after which White's initiative fades. }
12. Nxe5
12. dxe5{ White wins the pawn back, but ends up in a much worse position. }
13. Qxe5
13. Re8{ Black takes over. }
