5. Bc4{ The so-called 'Double Pawn Sacrifice Variation' of the Göring Gambit. White is offering the second pawn on  b2 , aiming to take back with the other bishop. White gets serious compensation as his 3 minor pieces occupy active positions. }
5. d6{ At first sight, this move may seem too passive... but better safe than sorry! 😀 }( { My good friend and fellow Chessable author GM Erwin L'Ami went for another pawn during the Olympiad: }5...cxb2 6.Bxb2 Bb4+ 7.Nc3 Nf6 8.O-O Bxc3 9.Bxc3 d6 { , 0-1 (27),  El Jawich  (2276) -  L'Ami  (2639), Batumi 2018, but despite the fact that Black is 2 pawns up, the engines deem this position as slightly better for White after }10.Ng5! O-O 11.f4→ { with a dangerous attack. } )
6. O-O
6. Nf6{ Black can now do without the somewhat peculiar ... Qd7 , developping his pieces in a natural way. }
7. Nxc3
7. Be7{ The only thing that White has going for them is that they have the more active pieces, which is, in this case, not sufficient to make up for being a pawn down, though. }
8. h3
8. O-O
9. Bf4
9. Nd7{ The Israelian Grandmaster is successfully regrouping his pieces, giving them more possibilities. }
10. Nd5
10. Nde5{ The initiative is fading and Black is still a pawn up. ½-½ (89),  Theodorou  (2577) -  Postny  (2557), Warsaw 2021. }
