1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. Bb5{ White's plan is, sooner or later, to take on  c6  and enjoy a structural plus. Compared to the Ruy Lopez,  central pawn breaks ( c3 + d4 ) are less common in the Four Knights Spanish, and instead, it often leads to more closed and manoeuvring games. }
4. Nd4{ We enter the 'Rubinstein Variation', named after the great  Akiba Rubinstein  - one of the great players in chess history (like  Paul Keres  and  Viktor Korchnoi ) who played at World Champion level but never got the title.    An old line, played in the late 19th century by the pioneers Marshall, Schlechter and Blackburne. This variation is to my taste as it seeks activity, breaking the symmetry. Black takes the lead while the bishop is somewhat misplaced on  b5 . }( { The main line and the only one I always have played, was }4...Bb4 5.O-O O-O 6.d3 d6 7.Bg5 Bxc3 8.bxc3 Qe7 9.Re1 Nd8!? { One of the key ideas - bringing the knight to the strong  e6 -square. }10.d4 Bg4 { My pet line.  10...Ne6  is more common. }11.h3 Bh5 12.g4 Bg6 13.d5 c6 14.Bd3 ( 14.Bc4 Rc8 15.Re3 cxd5 16.Bxd5 Ne6⩱ { , 0-1 (40),  Willemze  (2414) -  Werle  (2552), Netherlands 2007. } )14...Rc8 15.c4 b6= { ½-½ (66),  Adams  (2699) -  Werle  (2575), London 2009. } )
5. Ba4
5. Bc5{ Another active move, unleashing the beast, though leaving the  e5 -pawn unguarded. }
6. Nxe5{ Not to much to my surprise, taking on  e5  is the most popular line for White. The pawn was 'en price' - this provocation cannot be tolerated! However, this move implies that White is crossing the Rubicon. }
6. O-O{ We are showing our cards: we play on the quick development of our pieces! }
7. Nd3
7. Bb6{ Although White could retreat winning a tempo forcing ... Bb6 , the next problems arises: how should he develop his  c1 -bishop now? }
8. e5
8. Ne8{ Intending to bring the knight 'back on track' by ... d6 . }
9. Nd5{ With the multiple purposes of chasing the knight by  c2 - c3  and exchanging an attacker on  b6 . }
9. d6{ Liberating the pieces. }
10. Ne3
10. c5{ This move scores best, placing the bishop on  c7  while impeding any  c3 - d4  advance in the center. }
11. c3
11. Nf5{ It is clear that White is way down on development. }
12. O-O( 12.Bc2 { fails to impress me. Black easily neutralizes White's opening initiative with }12...Nxe3 13.dxe3 c4 14.Nb4 dxe5 15.Qxd8 Bxd8 16.e4 Nf6= { . } )
12. Nxe3{ With the aim to gain territory by ... c5 - c4 . }
13. dxe3( 13.fxe3 c4!=  )
13. c4{ This gains space, but makes the  d5 -square weak. As we will see, concrete factors often outweigh positional considerations! }
14. Nb4( { Black is doing more than fine after }14.Nf4 dxe5 15.Qxd8 Bxd8 16.Nd5 Be6 17.e4 Nd6 { . } )
14. dxe5
15. Qh5{  Shirov 's attractive playing style made him play this attacking move. }( { It is probably better to exchange queens with }15.Qxd8 Bxd8 { , but White has no hopes of an advantage after }16.e4 Nf6 { either }{ , ½-½ (42),  Doukhine  (2315) -  Romanov  (2408), Serpukhov 2004. } )
15. f5{ We seize the moment as White has not yet played  e4 , which means that the  c1 -bishop is still passive. }
16. Rd1
16. Nf6{ A clever intervention, regaining control over  d5 . }
17. Rxd8
17. Nxh5{ White is still burdened with his weak queenside pieces. }
18. Rd5
18. e4
19. Bb5{ ½-½ (28),  Shirov  (2710) -  Lautier  (2655), Monte Carlo 1995. }
19. Be6{ Of course, this improvement over the game  Shirov  -  Lautier  stems from the engine. }
20. Re5
20. Rad8{ The counterattack has been heralded. }
21. g4
21. Bf7{ A fantastic move to reroute the bishop to the kingside, leaving the knight en prise! }( { A correspondence game continued }22.gxh5 Rd1+ 23.Kg2 Bxh5 24.f4 Bf3+ 25.Kg3 Bd8 26.Nd5 Kh8 27.Ne7 Rf6 28.Be8 Rfd6 29.Ba4 Rh1 30.Rd5 Bxe7 31.Rxd6 Rg1+ 32.Kf2 Rg2+ 33.Kf1 Rxh2 { followed by ... Rh1 + and ... Bh4  mate! 0-1 (33)  Kirk  (1573) -  Houglan , ICCF email 2019. } )
