4. exd4
5. Nxd4( { Playing  1..e5  against a lower-rated opponent, I came across this line time to time. Playing the main line with }5...Bb4 { , I could hardly reach a position where there was enough space to have a real fight. Therefore, I give you the following sharp variation in order to dodge the white players aiming for a draw. } )
5. Nxe4( { Recently, I became aware of the existence of this line when my student Tom played it during his first round at the Dutch Championships U16. Initially, I thought he had made up something himself, but he later explained to me that it was actually a modern line. For example, }5...Bb4 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.exd5 cxd5 9.O-O O-O 10.Bg5 c6 11.Qf3 Bd6 12.Rae1 h6 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Qxf6 gxf6 15.Ne2 c5 16.Ng3= { , ½-½ (42),  Smerdon  (2466) -  Werle  (2568), Hoogeveen 2007. } )
6. Nxe4
6. Qe7{ At first sight, you may think that your author is an amateur putting his queen out so early in the game. But as we dig a bit deeper, you will figure that this variation is not so bad as it seems. }
7. f3( { Black is simply a pawn up after }7.Nxc6? Qxe4+! 8.Be2 dxc6 9.O-O Be6∓ { . } )
7. d5{ It's necessary to win back the piece with this pin - we have no choice and accept White's next move  Bb5 . }
8. Bb5
8. Bd7{ When I saw my student Tom playing this line for the first time, I was a bit flabbergasted and convinced that he ended up straight from the opening in a much worse position. My premature verdict was: the black king has nowhere to hide! }
9. Bxc6( { The line }9.O-O dxe4 10.Bxc6 bxc6 { leads to a transposition. White should avoid   }10.Nxc6? Qc5+! 11.Nd4 Bxb5∓ { . } )
9. bxc6{ Let's take stock of our position. After regaining the knight, White will attempt to target our king along the e-file. We will not find the time to shelter his Royal Highness at  g8 , but long castling can serve us well. Even there, we must be alert on strikes due to our weakened king's position by the doubled pawns. }
10. O-O
10. dxe4{ White is betting on the Black's stuck king and the misplaced black pieces. And indeed, analysing this position with my student Tom, I genuinely believed that Black could hardly survive. I was wrong. }
11. fxe4{ At least the e-file is closed now and the worst of all the dangers has disappeared. }
11. c5( { We are driving the knight from its dominant position. White has 3 options here: }12.Nb3 { , }12.Nf5 { and }12.Nf3 { . } )( 11...g6?! { is less to my taste. White could be slightly better after }12.Nb3! Bg7 13.Be3 Be6 14.Qc1⩲ { . } )
12. Nf5
12. Qe6{ Rock solid, glueing everything together. The queen seems impeccably placed at  e6 . }
13. Bf4
13. O-O-O{ Finally we managed to castle long. Even though the king is exposed by the doubled pawns, it can't be engaged on easily by our opponent. }
14. Qf3
14. g6{ In comparision to the game  Karjakin - Vallejo Pons , Black is doing better off chasing the knight first. }( 14...Bc6 15.Rae1 g6 16.Qc3 f6 17.Qa5 Rd7 18.Qa6+ Kb8 19.Rf3 Bd5 20.Qb5+ Bb7 21.Rb3 Qxb3 22.axb3 { 1-0 (22),  Karjakin  (2753) -  Vallejo Pons  (2695), St Petersburg 2018. } )
15. Ne3
15. Re8{ Targetting  e4 . }
16. e5
16. Bc6{ The bishop is just too strong. }
