9. Bxc6( { The line }9.O-O dxe4 10.Bxc6 bxc6 { leads to a transposition. White should avoid   }10.Nxc6? Qc5+! 11.Nd4 Bxb5∓ { . } )
9. bxc6{ Let's take stock of our position. After regaining the knight, White will attempt to target our king along the e-file. We will not find the time to shelter his Royal Highness at  g8 , but long castling can serve us well. Even there, we must be alert on strikes due to our weakened king's position by the doubled pawns. }
10. O-O
10. dxe4{ White is betting on the Black's stuck king and the misplaced black pieces. And indeed, analysing this position with my student Tom, I genuinely believed that Black could hardly survive. I was wrong. }
11. Re1{ This is obviously the most direct reaction to Black's provocative play. }
11. O-O-O{ Our position still looks rather ugly, and the king unsafe. Playing with such a weakened queenside is uncompromising. }
12. Rxe4
12. Qb4{ We are still following the main stream theory (considering this modern line). This strange engine-produced move is the only and 25-folded played move here! The queen is using the check against the white king. }
13. Nb3{ The most concrete continuation, hitting the queen meanwhile pointing the kinght at the our weak squares  c5  and  a5 . }
13. Qb7
14. Re1
14. Be6
15. Qe2
15. Bxb3{ This move is so off the chart ugly and bad that it's good: Black gets to place his rook on  e8  with tempo. }
16. axb3
16. Bb4{ If White manages to consolidate, they will have the advantage in the endgame. Needless to say, we won't let them! }
17. c3
17. Rhe8
18. Qxe8( 18.Qf2? Bc5!  )
18. Rxe8
19. Rxe8+
19. Kd7
20. Re1
20. Bc5+{ Picking up the  b3 -pawn next. It's usually better to have the two rooks against the queen, but in this case, the rooks don't coordinate and have no attacking targets. }
