4. exd4
5. Nd5( { The Belgrade Gambit is an aggressive line that derives from the Four Knights Game with a hint of Scotch sauce. However, the Belgrade Gambit is a distant second in popularity to }5.Nxd4 { . } )
5. Nb4{ This is an aggressive variation, encountering White's obstructive  d5 -knight. It is in line with our repertoire: looking for active solutions to the opening issues posed by White. The first game seen with  5...Nb4  was from  Bozidar Markov . }( 5...Be7 { is not as convincing as  5...Nb4 : it's somewhat passive but on the other hand, quite solid. For instance, }6.Bd3 d6 7.h3 O-O 8.O-O Be6 9.Nxe7+ Qxe7 10.Bg5 { and White had some compensation for the pawn in  Naroditsky  (2616) -  Paravyan  (2617), 0-1 (51), chess.com 2022. } )
6. Nxf6+
6. Qxf6{ The funny thing is that the pawn at  d4  is untouchable due to a silly fork at  c2 . }
7. a3( 7.Nxd4?? Qxd4 { loses on the spot for White. } )
7. Nc6{ This line has been tested a couple of times by some strong GMs in recent internet games. }
8. Bg5
8. Qg6
9. Bd3
9. d6{ White can't profit from the fact that the queen is at  g6 . }
10. e5
10. Bf5( 10...Qe6 { was also playable }{ . } )
11. O-O
11. dxe5{ Followed by ... Bd6  leaves Black with two pawns up without compensation.  GM Cori  realised this and offered a draw against a lower-rated opponent in  Cori  (2647) -  Rojas Salas  (2210), ½-½ (12), Lima 2022. }
