5. Nb4{ This is an aggressive variation, encountering White's obstructive  d5 -knight. It is in line with our repertoire: looking for active solutions to the opening issues posed by White. The first game seen with  5...Nb4  was from  Bozidar Markov . }( 5...Be7 { is not as convincing as  5...Nb4 : it's somewhat passive but on the other hand, quite solid. For instance, }6.Bd3 d6 7.h3 O-O 8.O-O Be6 9.Nxe7+ Qxe7 10.Bg5 { and White had some compensation for the pawn in  Naroditsky  (2616) -  Paravyan  (2617), 0-1 (51), chess.com 2022. } )
6. Nxd4
6. Nxe4{ A pawn is a pawn, so let's take it! }
7. Nb5{ Attacking  c7 . }
7. Nxd5
8. Qxd5{ This system is quite tricky, as we can't retreat our knight to  f6  due to a nasty check on  e5 . }
8. Qe7{ A very creative way to solve our opening problems. }( 8...Nf6 9.Qe5+!  )
9. Nxc7+
9. Kd8{ As a result of the imminent discovered check, White should refrain from taking on  a8 . }
10. Bf4{ Building a 'bridge' on  e5 , defending against the check. }
10. d6{ Attacking the knight, and reinventing the threat of winning the queen by ... Nc3 +. }( 10...Nc3+? 11.Qe5! { when White is suddenly winning. } )
11. O-O-O
11. Kxc7{ We should remain vigilant, as the attack is still in progress. }
12. Bc4
12. g5{ Hunting down White's most active minor piece. }
13. Be3
13. Nc5{ We are ready for ... Be6  now - things start looking good for us! }
14. Bxg5
14. Be6( 14...Qe4 { was possible as well }{ . } )
15. Bxe7
15. Bxd5{ 4 bishops are hanging! 😮 }
16. Bxd6+
16. Bxd6
17. Rxd5
17. Rae8{ White lacked real compensation for the sacrificed piece in  Robledo  }{ (2295) }{ -  Stratta  }{ (2271) }{ , 0-1, ICCF email 2006. }
