1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. g3{ By playing  4.g3 , White is aiming to fianchetto their bishop on  g2 , which can control important central squares and put pressure on Black's queenside.    This move is a flexible choice for White, as it can lead to a variety of different pawn structures and strategic plans depending on Black's response. }
4. Bc5
5. Bg2
5. d6
6. d3
6. a5{ Although this move is not commonly used, I decided to choose it over the other 6(!) more popular moves. The reason for my decision will be explained in the selected games.    By making this move, the knight gains the freedom to move to  a4  without leaving  e4  vulnerable, which allows for a trade with the powerful  c5 -bishop.     Duda  and  Yu  Yanghi have demonstrated that choosing  6...a5  instead of the more commonly used  6...a6  can lead to Black benefiting from future expansion on the queenside. }( 6...a6 7.O-O O-O 8.Kh1 Ng4 9.Qe1 f5!?∞ { , 0-1 (85),  Wei Yi  (2736) -  Firouzja  (2682), chess.com 2019. } )
7. Be3
7. Bxe3{ Our stem game  Rapport - Duda , 2022, points out that  fxe3  proves a serious weakening for White. }
8. fxe3{ At first sight, White seems to be doing fine, as the opened f-file can be used for attacking purposes. }
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Ne7{ The right plan: moving the knight towards the kingside, preparing for ... c7 - c6 . }
10. Nh4
10. c6{ Followed by ... d6 - d5  soon. }( {  Petrov  plays this position in great style and shows how dangerous Black's initiative on the queenside can become: }11.Nf5 g6 12.Nxe7+ Qxe7 13.d4 ( 13.a4 h5!∓  )13...b5! { ∓ }{ , 0-1 (43).  Hulshof  (2192) -  Petrov  (2592), Lisbon 2020. } )
