2. Bc4( { This is called the Bishop's Opening, a fairly respected sideline. White mainly plays it to avoid the Petroff Defense }{ ( }2.Nf3 Nf6 { ) }{ . } )
2. Nf6{ A concrete approach, attacking a pawn while developing our knight. }
3. Nc3
3. Nxe4( { Apparently, this is called the 'Dracula-Frankenstein Variation'. I'm also learning every day.    }3...Nc6 { may be  the easiest solution . White doesn't have much else than }4.d4 { , returning to the Vienna Opening. }4.d3 ( 4.Nf3 Nxe4! { transposes to the  Four Knights Game  chapter. } )4...Bc5 { , when we transpose to the Italian Opening, }{ but White has some extra options because he hasn't played  Nf3  yet. One of them is }5.Bg5!? { , which is specifically what we try to avoid in our Italian repertoire with   }5...h6 { . }{ Moreover, I want to avoid the Vienna ... Bc5  lines by playing a quick ... Na5xc4 . } )
4. Qh5
4. Nd6
5. Bb3
5. Nc6( { This sharp move implies the  exchange sacrifice  }5...Nc6 6.Nb5 g6 7.Qf3 f5 8.Qd5 Qe7 9.Nxc7+ Kd8 10.Nxa8 b6 { . } )( { The calmer alternative is }5...Be7 { followed by ... O-O . } )
6. Nb5{ An ultimate attempt to revive the scholar's mate. }
6. g6{ Slowly pushing our opponent back. }( { Please don't fall for }6...Be7?? 7.Nxd6+ Bxd6 8.Qxf7# { ! } )
7. Qf3( { After }7.Nxd6+? Bxd6∓ { , we are a healthy pawn up. } )
7. f5( { The queen can't defend  f7  with }7...Qe7 { , because White would take on  c7 : }8.Nxc7+ { . } )
8. Qd5{ Once again, we can't afford even the slightest misstep. }
8. Qe7{ Just leaving the pawn and the rook on  c7  and  a8  'en prise'! Black will gain the knight back by putting his bishop on  b7 . }
9. Nxc7+
9. Kd8
10. Nxa8
10. b6{ The bishop is directed to the long diagonal. }
11. Qd3
11. Bb7{ This is a monster on the long diagonal. }
12. Nxb6
12. axb6{ Yes, White is winning a pawn. On the other hand, he is losing valuable time here. }
13. Ne2
13. f4
14. O-O
14. h5{ Almost only correspondence games have been played here. The position on the board is from another planet. }
15. f3
15. Nf5{ We can take several serious attacking ideas into consideration. Maybe the most important is to move the bishop to  c5  chasing the king to the corner. From there, we would like to devour the cornered animal by ... Qh4  and ... Ng3 +. }( 16.Qb5 Qc5+ { and, surprisingly enough, even after the exchange of queens, Black can proceed with his perilous attack. }17.Qxc5 Bxc5+ 18.Rf2 { , the only move. }( { After }18.Kh1 h4 { , }{ White is suffering a quick due to ... Ng3 +. }19.d3 Ng3+ 20.Nxg3 hxg3 21.h3 Nd4 22.c3 Nxf3 23.gxf3 { (Black was threatening }23.-- Rxh3+ 24.gxh3 Nh4+ { )   }23...Rxh3+ 24.Kg2 Rh2# { . } )18...h4 19.c3 g5 { , }{ protecting  f4  and keeping the  c1 -bishop 'in the box'. }20.Bd5 Ba6=∞ { , with excellent compensation for the pawn. }{ We intend to put the bishop on  d3 , as Morphy did in his famous game of 1857 against Paulsen. ½-½ (31),  Czudek  (2078) -  Lanzani  (2217), ICCF email 2017. } )
