3. Nxe4( { Apparently, this is called the 'Dracula-Frankenstein Variation'. I'm also learning every day.    }3...Nc6 { may be  the easiest solution . White doesn't have much else than }4.d4 { , returning to the Vienna Opening. }4.d3 ( 4.Nf3 Nxe4! { transposes to the  Four Knights Game  chapter. } )4...Bc5 { , when we transpose to the Italian Opening, }{ but White has some extra options because he hasn't played  Nf3  yet. One of them is }5.Bg5!? { , which is specifically what we try to avoid in our Italian repertoire with   }5...h6 { . }{ Moreover, I want to avoid the Vienna ... Bc5  lines by playing a quick ... Na5xc4 . } )
4. Qh5
4. Nd6
5. Bb3
5. Nc6( { This sharp move implies the  exchange sacrifice  }5...Nc6 6.Nb5 g6 7.Qf3 f5 8.Qd5 Qe7 9.Nxc7+ Kd8 10.Nxa8 b6 { . } )( { The calmer alternative is }5...Be7 { followed by ... O-O . } )
6. Nb5{ An ultimate attempt to revive the scholar's mate. }
6. g6{ Slowly pushing our opponent back. }( { Please don't fall for }6...Be7?? 7.Nxd6+ Bxd6 8.Qxf7# { ! } )
7. Qf3( { After }7.Nxd6+? Bxd6∓ { , we are a healthy pawn up. } )
7. f5( { The queen can't defend  f7  with }7...Qe7 { , because White would take on  c7 : }8.Nxc7+ { . } )
8. Qd5{ Once again, we can't afford even the slightest misstep. }
8. Qe7{ Just leaving the pawn and the rook on  c7  and  a8  'en prise'! Black will gain the knight back by putting his bishop on  b7 . }
9. Nxc7+
9. Kd8
10. Nxa8
10. b6{ The bishop is directed to the long diagonal. }
11. d3
11. Nd4( { This move is stronger than the main line }11...Bb7 { . White gets some attacking chances after }12.h4!? { . } )
12. Nh3
12. f4( { Using a similar plan − restricting White's minor pieces. Please don't act too hastily! }12...Bb7?? 13.Qxb7! Nxb7 14.Bg5+- { . } )
13. Nxb6
13. axb6{ Once more the queen is in danger of being trapped by ... Bb7 . }
14. Qa8
14. Kc7{ With loads of complications arising. }
