4. Nc3( { White has plenty of choice here. Let's take a quick look at the alternatives: }4.Nf3 Bc5 { brings us back to the Italian Opening. } )( 4.c3?! d5! { nicely shows how quickly White can lose the initiative. }5.exd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Nb6 7.Bb3 Bf5 { is even slightly better for Black. } )( 4.a3?! d5! 5.exd5 Nxd5 6.Nf3 Bg4↑ { is very similar to  4.c3 . } )( 4.f4 { is an attempt to combine the Bishop's Opening and the Vienna. }4...exf4 5.Bxf4 d5! { Strike while the iron is hot! }6.exd5 Nxd5 7.Bxd5 { ( }7.Qe2+ Be6⩱ { )   }7...Qxd5 { . Of course, this can't be good for White. For instance, }8.Qe2+ Be6 9.Bxc7? Rc8∓ { . } )
4. Na5{ I fancy this concrete approach for Black, trading the powerful bishop on  c4 . }
5. Nge2
5. Nxc4{ Wreaking havoc to White's pawn structure. The damage in the shape of the doubled pawns is not the end of the universe for our opponent. In return, he can exert pressure across the open d-file. }
