2. Nf6( { The most direct approach - putting pressure on the  e4 -pawn. I feel this is more to the point than }2...Nc6 { . } )
3. Bc4{ We are entering the Stanley Variation of the Vienna Gambit. But who's  Stanley ?!     Charles Henry Stanley  was the unofficial United States' champion from 1845 until 1857. He gained the title by defeating  Eugene Rousseau  15 to 8. }( 3.Nf3 Nc6 { would transpose to the Four Knights Opening. } )
3. Nc6( { I also covered the  sharp alternative  }3...Nxe4 { in the  Bishop’s Opening  2.Bc4   chapter. }3...Nxe4 { is an ambitious move that tries to exploit White's move order, whereas }3...Nc6 { is the easy solution, because it will likely transpose to the Vienna Opening or Four Knights Game. The choice is yours! } )( { The second game of their match went }3...Bc5 4.Nf3 d6 5.h3 O-O 6.d3 Be6 7.Bb3⩲ { White had a tiny advantage. }7...Nc6 8.Ne2 Qe7 9.Ng3 Nd4 10.Nxd4 Bxd4 11.c3 Bb6 12.O-O d5? 13.Bg5! c6 14.Nh5 dxe4 15.dxe4 Bxb3 16.Qf3! Bc4 17.Bxf6 Qe6 18.Nxg7 Be2 19.Nxe6 Bxf3 20.Nxf8 { 1-0,  Stanley  -  Rousseau , New Orleans 1845. } )
4. d3( 4.Nf3 {  transposes  to the Italian Opening of the Four Knights. }4...Nxe4!  )
4. Na5{ We get the chance to exchange the bishop, thereby taking the sting out of White's attack. }
5. Nge2
5. Bc5{ We are waiting for one move to take on  c4 . Our intentions are to discourage White from castling long. }( { The immediate }5...Nxc4 { unnecessarily gives White some extra options, such as }6.dxc4 Bc5 7.Qd3 { , intending to castle queenside. } )
6. h3{ White is building a barricade on the light squares. }
6. d6
7. Ng3
7. Nxc4
8. dxc4
8. Be6
9. Qd3
9. O-O
10. b3
10. c6{ We are preparing a break in the center, as we are better developed and have the two bishops. }
11. O-O
11. d5{ Just in time! }
12. cxd5
12. cxd5
13. exd5
13. Nxd5{ Black is already better. The position resembles a Sicilian Defense, which was very poorly handled by White. }
