[White "E3) 1.e4 e5 Without 2.Nf3 – King’s Gambit 2.f4"]
[Black "1.e4 e5 Without 2.Nf3 – King’s Gambit 2.f4 d5 – 4.Nf3 #17"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. f4
2. d5{ I recommend the so-called 'Falkbeer Countergambit' since I don't want to allow White to do the attacking - we are going after White's king. }
3. exd5( 3.d4? { is simply bad. }3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.e5 Ne4∓ { White clearly faces some serious challenges in this position. } )
3. exf4{ A committing move as it determines the pawn structure for the long haul. Black is giving his center in return for two kingside pawns. }( { Another popular (main) line is }3...e4 4.d3 Nf6 5.dxe4 Nxe4 6.Be3 { when there are a lot of moves, plans and variations to study, 0-1 (31),  Rapport  (2763) -  Nihal  (2650), chess.com 2021. } )
4. Nf3{ The King's Gambit is one of the pet lines of World Title Challenger  Nepo . I didn't see him trying out this gambit in the Candidates, but nonetheless, he sees potential in this opening as he released a course about this opening lately. Beyond all the difficult lines we study here, even more reason to take this gambit seriously! }
4. Nf6{ With the idea to take on  d5 , immediately protecting the  f4 -pawn. }
5. Bb5+
5. c6{ We should forget about winning the  d5 -pawn, and prioritise developing our pieces. }
6. dxc6
6. Nxc6{ At least the knights are out. Through dogmatic spectacles, White has the preferable position due to his better pawn structure... can we even maintain the  f4 -pawn? }
7. Nc3{ I can appreciate that  Nepo  played this position several times, underlining his attractive playing style. And apparently, he believes in the King's Gambit. }
7. Be6{ A relatively unknown line. }( { The main line goes }7...Bd6 8.Qe2+ Be6 9.Nd4 O-O 10.Nxe6 fxe6 11.Bxc6 bxc6 12.b3 { with the idea of castling long, 1-0 (36),  Nepomniachtchi  (2773) - Demchenko  (2654), chess.com 2022. } )
8. O-O
8. Bd6{ Clinging on to the  f4 -pawn. }
9. d4
9. O-O( 9...a6? { was a total mishit in  Sobolewski  -  Golecka , 1-0 (28), Warsaw 2011. }10.Bxc6+ bxc6 11.Ng5! { Black unnecessarily got in trouble. } )
10. Ne2
10. Nh5{ We hold on to the  f4 -pawn, all set to launch an attack by ... g7 - g5 - g4 . }
11. c4( 11.c3 g5!→ { greatly troubles White's development. } )
11. a6
12. Bxc6
12. bxc6{ We have the bishop pair and a lead in development, as White's  c1 -bishop hasn't found its purpose yet. ... g5  and ... Re8  will be easy moves to make. }
