[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. d4( { This opening is called 'The Center Game'. It was one of my favourite openings as a child, especially due to the response of my opponents. They didn't want to give up on castling after }2...d6 3.dxe5 dxe5 { and }4.Qxd8+ Kxd8 { , so instead, they chose  2...f6 , which didn't turn out in their favour. } )
2. exd4{ Just so you know, we are entering the Center Game Accepted. }( 2...f6? 3.dxe5 fxe5 4.Qh5+ { Black has to make a devil's choice between  4...g6  and  4...Ke7 : }4...Ke7 5.Qxe5+ Kf7 6.Bc4+ Kg6 7.Qf5# { with a mate! }{    Or   }4...g6 5.Qxe5+ { wins the  h8 -rook. } )
3. c3{ After  3.c3 , the Center Game changes colour to the Danish Gambit. The Gambit resembles the Göring Gambit but  Nf3  and ... Nc6  haven't been played yet. }( 3.Nf3 Nc6 { is the goat path to our main lines. For example, }4.Bc4 Nf6 { leads us to the Scotch Gambit,      }4.c3 { is the  Göring Gambit ,      }4.Nxd4 { is the  main line of the Scotch . } )
3. dxc3
4. Bc4( { White aims for super quick development. Many interesting lines could arise, for instance by accepting the gift with }4...cxb2 { . } )( { My main objective is to teach you lines that are easy to remember. We will not dodge any transpositions! }4.Nxc3 Nc6 5.Nf3 d6 6.Bc4 Nf6 { would transpose to the Göring Gambit again. } )
4. Nc6{ In this jungle of variations, I would like to keep it simple by transposing to the Göring Gambit. }
5. Nxc3( 5.Nf3 d6 { would again transpose to the Göring Gambit. } )
5. Nf6
6. Nf3
6. d6{ I think you can guess to which opening we have transposed by now. }
