1. e4
1. e5
2. d4( { This opening is called 'The Center Game'. It was one of my favourite openings as a child, especially due to the response of my opponents. They didn't want to give up on castling after }2...d6 3.dxe5 dxe5 { and }4.Qxd8+ Kxd8 { , so instead, they chose  2...f6 , which didn't turn out in their favour. } )
2. exd4{ Just so you know, we are entering the Center Game Accepted. }( 2...f6? 3.dxe5 fxe5 4.Qh5+ { Black has to make a devil's choice between  4...g6  and  4...Ke7 : }4...Ke7 5.Qxe5+ Kf7 6.Bc4+ Kg6 7.Qf5# { with a mate! }{    Or   }4...g6 5.Qxe5+ { wins the  h8 -rook. } )
3. Qxd4( 3.Nf3 Nc6 { is the goat path to our main lines. For example, }4.Bc4 Nf6 { leads us to the Scotch Gambit,      }4.c3 { is the  Göring Gambit ,      }4.Nxd4 { is the  main line of the Scotch . } )
3. Nc6{ Once I faced an opponent of higher age and calibre, I faced this unpleasant move. White is losing valuable time with the queen while Black is playing a useful developing move with the knight. }
4. Qc4{ You may be surprised to hear that this utterly strange and new move has been tried out by top players like  Carlsen ,  Fedoseev  and  Wei Yi ! }
4. Nf6
5. Nc3{ My teammate  Lucas van Foreest  was quite enthusiastic about this White configuration of pieces. I never really understood if he was serious 😀 Obviously, White's opening only has surprise value. }
5. Bb4
6. Bd2{ By far the most played, as well as frequently on the top level. }
6. O-O
7. O-O-O
7. Re8{ Threatening to take on  c3  and then on  e4 . }( 7...d6 { is playable too. }8.f3 Be6 { and we can proceed with our typical play using ... a7 - a5 , ... c7 - c6 , and ... b7 - b5  to gain a strong initiative. 0-1  Fedoseev  (2687) -  Artemiev  (2709), lichess.org 2021. } )
8. f3{ Another pawn move, slowing down White's development. }
8. a5{ The best move. }( { 'Mainstream theory' in this offbeat system (is this a contradictio in terminis?) is }8...d6 9.Qe2!? ( 9.g4 { was unsuccessfully tried by  Carlsen , 0-1 (17),  Carlsen  (2862) -  Tang  (2538), lichess.org 2021. } )9...d5!⩱ { White's coordination is a mess. } )
9. a3
9. d6{ Making use of the vulnerable position of the king. }
10. Qa2( { White can better refrain from being greedy by accepting the gift. For example, }10.axb4 axb4 11.Nb1 Be6 12.Qe2 Ra1-+ { followed by ... Ba2 . } )
10. Ne5{ Discouraging  Bc4  and preparing for ... Be6 . }
11. Bc4{ What else? Allowing ... Be6   Qa1  is painful.    0-1 (18),  Ehlvest  (2517) -  Moradiabadi  (2555), chess.com 2020. }
11. c6{ Our queenside attack should prove decisive, and our next moves will follow naturally. }
