2. d4( { This opening is called 'The Center Game'. It was one of my favourite openings as a child, especially due to the response of my opponents. They didn't want to give up on castling after }2...d6 3.dxe5 dxe5 { and }4.Qxd8+ Kxd8 { , so instead, they chose  2...f6 , which didn't turn out in their favour. } )
2. exd4{ Just so you know, we are entering the Center Game Accepted. }( 2...f6? 3.dxe5 fxe5 4.Qh5+ { Black has to make a devil's choice between  4...g6  and  4...Ke7 : }4...Ke7 5.Qxe5+ Kf7 6.Bc4+ Kg6 7.Qf5# { with a mate! }{    Or   }4...g6 5.Qxe5+ { wins the  h8 -rook. } )
3. Qxd4( 3.Nf3 Nc6 { is the goat path to our main lines. For example, }4.Bc4 Nf6 { leads us to the Scotch Gambit,      }4.c3 { is the  Göring Gambit ,      }4.Nxd4 { is the  main line of the Scotch . } )
3. Nc6{ Once I faced an opponent of higher age and calibre, I faced this unpleasant move. White is losing valuable time with the queen while Black is playing a useful developing move with the knight. }
4. Qe3{ The main line of the Center Gambit. White intends to stop ... d7 - d5 , claiming a space advantage in the center. }
4. Nf6{ Surprisingly, this line has been tried in practice by many elite players, among who are  Nepo ,  Aronian  and  Artemiev . }
5. Nc3
5. Bb4{ We strive for a quick development by ... Bb4 , ... O-O  and ... Re8 . Ideally, we are sparing one move on ... d7 - d6  in order to advance it to  d5  without delay. }( { The line }5...Be7 6.Bd2 { would transpose to   5.Bd2  . } )
6. Bd2{ This is by far the most popular move amongst top players. }
6. O-O{ We are completing the development and are poised to play ... d7 - d5 . }
7. O-O-O
7. Re8{ Trying to exploit the vulnerable position of the queen before we play ... d5 . }
8. Qg3
8. Nxe4{ This move scores even better than  8...Rxe4 , which has been tested a lot on a high level. }( 8...Rxe4!? { , with the idea that after }9.Nxe4 Nxe4 { White is subjected to a double attack, is also interesting. Therefor, White plays   }9.a3 { instead (1-0 (32),  Nepomniachtchi  (2776) -  Ding  (2811), chess.com 2019.) } )
9. Nxe4
9. Rxe4{ The rook might be subjected to all kinds of threats, as it is vulnerable on  e4 . Nonetheless, things are not that easy for White. For instance, in case of  Bd3 , Black takes on  d2 , when  Rxd2  is answered by ... Re1 +. }
10. Bf4{ Hitting  c7 . }
10. Qf6{ Piece activity is more important than material. }
11. Nh3( 11.Bxc7? d6!-+ { The bishop is trapped. } )
11. d6
12. Bd3
12. Nd4{ A fierce battle for the initiative is ongoing, with White attempting to prove his compensation for the pawn. The knight is bothering White since he should reckon with the fork at  e2 . }
13. Kb1
13. Ne2
14. Qf3
14. Ba3{ Suddenly White's king is besieged from all angles. White has no choice but to take on  a3 . }
15. bxa3
15. Nc3+
16. Kc1
16. Nxa2+
17. Kb1( 17.Kd2 Qc3#  )
17. Nc3+
18. Kc1
18. Bxh3{ Eliminating the protector of the  f4 -bishop. }
19. Bxe4
19. Bxg2
20. Qxg2
20. Qxf4+
21. Kb2
21. Nxe4{ The resulting position is completely winning for Black, due to the many pawns and weak king. 0-1 (36)  Nepomniachtchi  (2587) -  Vallejo Pons  (2679), Moscow 2007. }
