[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. e5
2. Nf3
2. Nc6
3. c3{ The main idea behind the Ponziani is to control the center with the pawn on  d4 . This noble endeavor, however, has a clear disadvantage: the  c3 -square is not available for the knight.    While it is not a top choice among modern grandmasters, it can be a surprise weapon and a good option for club players who want to play something different. }
3. d5{ Strike while the iron is hot! }( { White cannot use the  c3 -square for their knight to chase the queen after }4.exd5 Qxd5 { , so we are taking control in the center. } )
4. exd5
4. Qxd5{ Most White players won't go for this line, as it hands over the initiative. The only thing we have to do is bring our bishop out and castle queenside. }
5. d4
5. Nf6
6. Be3
6. Bf5{ Preparing for long castling. }
7. Be2
7. exd4
8. cxd4( { Obviously, White can neither hope for something after }8.Bxd4 Nxd4 9.Qxd4 Bc5∓ { , 0-1 (29),  Nagy  (2100) -  Shishkov  (2291), ICCF email 2009. } )
8. Bxb1{ The cat is out of the bag! The venomous  6...Bf5  stopped White from playing  Nb1 - c3 . }
9. Rxb1
9. Bb4+{ In case the bishops are exchanged on  d2 , Black will eventually conquer the isolated pawn. }
