11. Nd7{ Honestly, this is one of my favorite lines. It features the elegant strategy of positioning the powerful bishop on  f6 , targeting  d4  yet again. At the same time, the knight on  d7  bolsters the central pawns on  e5  and  c5 . }
12. d5{ A key concept in this position is seizing space in the center. Interestingly, we're quite pleased that our light-squared bishop hasn't been moved; had it been on  c7 , it would be obstructed by the pawn. }( { In a similar position, Bacrot had previously opted for }12.Nbd2 { , preserving the tension in the center. } )
