27. Ne3( { This is forced, }27.Nxh6 Bxh6 { is almost dead lost already with the double threats of taking the knight on  d2  or pinning the rook on  g3 . } )
27. a5{ The rooks are wonderfully placed behind the pawns. }
28. h4
28. Nf7{ Black of course wants to play ... Bh6  followed by ... Bf4 , the knights don't have any good squares to go to and the cooperation between the pieces is almost non-existent. Black is definitely better. }
29. g5{ With the sole purpose of just making the position more difficult and double-edged, so I don't just conduct my operations unbothered. }
29. fxg5
30. hxg5
30. Ng7{ The knight is now activated through  h5  and  f4 . }
31. Ng2{ A very interesting plan by my talented opponent. He wants to prepare for  f4 . }
31. Be7
32. f4{ Fighting for the dark squares by putting all of the pawns there. In my opinion this is the only chance for white to keep fighting.     Up to this point I think the game was pretty flawless, but now comes the moment where I commit my first mistake. }
32. Rc8( { The better move was unpinning with }32...Kg8 { , because after this move there's not much that white can do,  ...Nh5  will come with full control over the dark squares for black. } )
33. Bb1
