8. Ba6
9. b3( 9.Qe4 Nb4! { and we have a lot of threats coming, we are threatening to play  ...d5  next. } )
9. g6
10. f4{ This is a very tricky line for black, every move here from now on is dangerous so we need to be careful and well-prepared.     }( 10.g3 { please refer to the model game  Rustam Kasimdzhanov - Jorden van Foreest.  } )
10. d6( { The first pitfall is already here, be careful of playing }10...Bg7 { because its too slow here, }11.Qf2 { the knight is hanging and we don't have time to take on  e5  like in the mainline with  10...d6 . The correct move order matters here! } )
11. Qf2
11. Nf6
12. Be2
12. dxe5
13. O-O( { The dangerous-looking bishop move }13.Ba3 { transposes to   12.Ba3  Qe6  13.Be2 dxe5  . }{ after }13...Qe6 { . } )
13. Ne4{ We have to play active! }
14. Qf3( 14.Qe1 { please refer to the theory! } )
14. f5{ Nailing the down on  e4 . }
15. Nc3
15. exf4{ Our plan is to keep the e-file closed for now, and then we need to find a way to put the dark-squared bishop on  d4  followed by  ...c5  in order to safely consolidate our king's position next. Let's see how Kramnik managed to do so in this game. }( { Please don't take on  c3  }15...Nxc3 16.Qxc3 Bg7 17.Qa5 { and  Ba3  coming in next, we are busted. } )
16. Nxe4
16. fxe4
17. Qxf4
17. Bg7
18. Ba3
18. Bd4+{ As planned, now both central files are closed. }
19. Kh1
19. c5
20. Rae1
20. Rf8
21. Qg4
21. Bc8( { Even better here is to take first }21...Rxf1 22.Rxf1 Rb8! { with the plan of putting the rook on  f6  to counter all of the threats of our opponents, we of course already discussed this in the theoretical part. } )
22. Rxf8+
22. Kxf8
23. Qf4+
23. Kg8
24. Rd1
24. g5{ The idea behind ... Kg8 , now the queen can go to  g7  to support the strong bishop on  d4 . }
25. Qg3
25. Qg7
26. b4( { Unfortunate mistake, }26.Bc1 { is still not easy for black, after }26...h6 { there's still }27.h4 { with a very unclear position. } )
26. Be6{ Kramnik gets the chance to consolidate, of course he doesn't care about the c-pawn. }
27. bxc5
27. Rb8{ For the price of one pawn, Kramnik got two very important developing moves! }
28. h3
28. Qe5
29. Qxe5
29. Bxe5
30. c6
30. Rb6{ A very nice move with a lot of threats! }
31. c5{ Did Kramnik miss this move since now we can't take on  c6  because the rook gets trapped after  Bb5 ? }
31. Rb8{ Of course not! All of this was part of his masterplan. He quietly returns and now white's queenside is completely exposed with the bishops shining all along the diagonals. While the bishop on  a3  is completely out of the game. }
32. Bc1
32. Bxa2
33. Bxg5
33. a5
34. Be7
34. Bb3{ There's no way to stop the a-pawn. }
35. Rf1
35. a4{ Nedev resigns, Kramnik played a model game in this Scotch Mainline! }
